{"title_page": "Portugal national under-17 basketball team", "text_new": "{{Infobox national basketball team\n| country            = Portugal \n| logo               = Flag of Portugal.svg\n| logo_width         = 130px \n| nickname           = \n| fiba_zone          = FIBA Europe\n| national_fed       = [[Portuguese Basketball Federation|Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Basquetebol]]\n| coach              = \n| wc_championship    = [[FIBA Under-17 Basketball World Cup|Under-17 World Cup]]\n| wc_appearances     = None \n| wc_medals          = \n| zone_championship  = [[FIBA U16 European Championship|U16 European Championship]]\n| zone_appearances   = 2\n| zone_medals        = None\n| zone_championship2 = [[FIBA U16 European Championship#Division B|U16 European Championship Division B]]\n| zone_appearances2  = 14\n| zone_medals2       = {{Eur2}} ''Silver:'' ([[2005 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship Division B|2005]])\n| h_body             = ffffff \n| h_shorts           = ffffff \n| h_pattern_b        = _greensides \n| h_pattern_s        = _greensides \n| a_body             = 990000 \n| a_shorts           = 990000\n| a_pattern_b        = _greensides \n| a_pattern_s        = _greensides \n}}\n\nThe '''Portugal national under-16 and under-17 basketball team''' is the national representative for [[Portugal]] in international under-16 and under-17 [[basketball]] competitions. They are controlled by the [[Portuguese Basketball Federation|Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Basquetebol]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Portugal (U16-U17)|url=https://www.eurobasket.com/Portugal/basketball-National-Team.asp?Age=16|accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe team competes at the [[FIBA U16 European Championship]], with the opportunity to qualify for the [[FIBA Under-17 Basketball World Cup|FIBA Under-17 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Portugal at the 2016 FIBA U16 European Championship Division B|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u16b/2016/Portugal|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Portugal at the 2017 FIBA U16 European Championship Division B|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u16b/2017/Portugal|accessdate=19 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Portugal national basketball team]]\n*[[Portugal national under-19 basketball team]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fpb.pt/ Official website] {{in lang|pt}}\n*[http://www.fiba.basketball/federation/Portugal FIBA profile]\n\n{{International youth basketball}}\n{{National sports teams of Portugal}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Portugal national basketball team}}\n[[Category:Basketball in Portugal]]\n[[Category:National under-16 basketball teams]]\n[[Category:National under-17 basketball teams]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of Portugal|Basketball]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox national basketball team\n| country            = Portugal \n| logo               = Flag of Portugal.svg\n| logo_width         = 130px \n| nickname           = \n| fiba_zone          = FIBA Europe\n| national_fed       = [[Portuguese Basketball Federation|Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Basquetebol]]\n| coach              = \n| wc_championship    = [[FIBA Under-17 Basketball World Cup|Under-17 World Cup]]\n| wc_appearances     = None \n| wc_medals          = \n| zone_championship  = [[FIBA U16 European Championship|U16 European Championship]]\n| zone_appearances   = 2\n| zone_medals        = None\n| zone_championship2 = [[FIBA U16 European Championship#Division B|U16 European Championship Division B]]\n| zone_appearances2  = 14\n| zone_medals2       = {{Eur2}} ''Silver:'' ([[2005 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship Division B|2005]])\n| h_body             = ffffff \n| h_shorts           = ffffff \n| h_pattern_b        = _greensides \n| h_pattern_s        = _greensides \n| a_body             = 990000 \n| a_shorts           = 990000\n| a_pattern_b        = _greensides \n| a_pattern_s        = _greensides \n}}\n\nThe '''Portugal national under-16 and under-17 basketball team''' is the national representative for [[Portugal]] in international under-16 and under-17 [[basketball]] competitions. They are controlled by the [[Portuguese Basketball Federation|Federa\u00e7\u00e3o Portuguesa de Basquetebol]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Portugal (U16-U17)|url=https://www.eurobasket.com/Portugal/basketball-National-Team.asp?Age=16|accessdate=15 October 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe team competes at the [[FIBA U16 European Championship]], with the opportunity to qualify for the [[FIBA Under-17 Basketball World Cup|FIBA Under-17 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Portugal at the 2016 FIBA U16 European Championship Division B|url=https://www.fiba.basketball/europe/u16b/2016/Portugal|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Portugal national basketball team]]\n*[[Portugal national under-19 basketball team]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fpb.pt/ Official website] {{in lang|pt}}\n*[http://www.fiba.basketball/federation/Portugal FIBA profile]\n\n{{International youth basketball}}\n{{National sports teams of Portugal}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Portugal national basketball team}}\n[[Category:Basketball in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Basketball teams in Portugal]]\n[[Category:National under-16 basketball teams]]\n[[Category:National under-17 basketball teams]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of Portugal|Basketball]]\n", "name_user": "SpinnDoctor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portugal_national_under-17_basketball_team"}
{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Pensione Haase, Salita del Petraio]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a lineal urban neighborhood and pedestrian path in [[Naples, Italy]].  It descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects adjacent neighborhoods to downtown Naples &mdash; terminating just outside the original perimeter walls of Naples,<ref name=\"pet13\"/> in present day's [[Chiaia]] district.\n\nFormerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally an ancient self-formed alluvial channel that followed a natural and narrow watershed &mdash; deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As the path was trafficked, inhabited and developed, it was improved to connect a rustic series of paved stone ''gradini'' (steps), ''descesa'' (descending steps), ''vici'' (alleys), ''largi'' (widenings), ''rampe'' (ramps) and ''salite'' (climbs) &mdash; varying in slope and width &mdash; and framed by buildings, churches,and small businesses.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\nAs one of roughly more than 200 neighborhood stairs, inclined walks and ramps in Naples,<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> the Petraio is accessible only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and broad views of the city and the ''[[Gulf of Naples|Golfo di Napoli]].''<ref name=\"pet12\">{{cite web\n |title        = Parcheggio selvaggio ai Gradini del Petraio \n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = March 2, 2017\n |url          = http://http://www.vomeromagazine.net/parcheggio-selvaggio-ai-gradini-del-petraio/}}</ref>\n\n==Access and sections==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed by Via Annibale Caccavello in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]] and the [[Montesanto Funicular]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]].<ref name=\"pet13\">{{cite web\n |title        = Percorsi segreti a Napoli: le scale del Petraio\n |publisher    = Latitudes Travel Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://www.latitudeslife.com/2019/04/napoli-scale-petraio/}}</ref> Midpoints of the Petraio are served directly by the other [[funicular]]s of Vomero: via the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] and the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' longest street, the prominent ''Corso Vittorio Emanuele''.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nProminent sub-sections include:\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of Genoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla, which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli.\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Pensione Haase, Salita del Petraio]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a lineal urban neighborhood and pedestrian path in [[Naples, Italy]].  It descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects adjacent neighborhoods to downtown Naples &mdash; terminating just outside the original perimeter walls of Naples,<ref name=\"pet13\"> in present day's [[Chiaia]] district.\n\nFormerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally an ancient self-formed alluvial channel that followed a natural and narrow watershed &mdash; deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As the path was trafficked, inhabited and developed, it was improved to connect a rustic series of paved stone ''gradini'' (steps), ''descesa'' (descending steps), ''vici'' (alleys), ''largi'' (widenings), ''rampe'' (ramps) and ''salite'' (climbs) &mdash; varying in slope and width &mdash; and framed by buildings, churches,and small businesses.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\nAs one of roughly more than 200 neighborhood stairs, inclined walks and ramps in Naples,<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> the Petraio is accessible only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and broad views of the city and the ''[[Gulf of Naples|Golfo di Napoli]].''<ref name=\"pet12\">{{cite web\n |title        = Parcheggio selvaggio ai Gradini del Petraio \n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = March 2, 2017\n |url          = http://http://www.vomeromagazine.net/parcheggio-selvaggio-ai-gradini-del-petraio/}}</ref>\n\n==Access and sections==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed by Via Annibale Caccavello in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]] and the [[Montesanto Funicular]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]].<ref name=\"pet13\">{{cite web\n |title        = Percorsi segreti a Napoli: le scale del Petraio\n |publisher    = Latitudes Travel Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://www.latitudeslife.com/2019/04/napoli-scale-petraio/}}</ref> Midpoints of the Petraio are served directly by the other [[funicular]]s of Vomero: via the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] and the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' longest street, the prominent ''Corso Vittorio Emanuele''.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref>\n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\nProminent sub-sections include:\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of Genoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla, which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli.\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
{"title_page": "Cosmetics in Korea", "text_new": "[[File:Korean cosmetics on a shelf.jpg|thumb|250px|Various Korean cosmetics products (peeling gel, essence, cleanser, toner, lotion and two types of creams) on a bathroom shelf]]\n\nKorea has an ancient history of cosmetics use, and today it is an important industry in South Korea.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Cosmetic box, stoneware with celadon glaze, Goryeo Dynasty.jpg|thumb|Goryeo Dynasty cosmetic box]]\n\n===Ancient times===\nRecords of the use of cosmetics in Korea date back to the time of the [[Three Kingdoms of Korea]], and the use of makeup flourished during the [[Goryeo kingdom]].{{cn|date=July 2017}} Cosmetics were made from lotions extracted from plants, including gourd stems; [[Mung bean|Ground mung bean]] contains [[saponin]] and was helpful for cleansing. [[Castor oil]]s and [[camellia oil]]s were used as hair oil. They had a pleasant smell and were not sticky. To moisturize and add gloss to the skin, safflower oil was used. [[Apricot]] and [[peach]] oils were used to remove freckles and liver spots. A powder called 'mibun' or 'baekbun' was made from ground rice and [[millet]] blended with water or oil.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2013/01/135_129776.html|title=Tracing history of cosmetics|website=the koreatimes|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nScents were added to extracts from grains and other plants, for example from dried clove buds. Perfume was also used to relieve stresses and tiredness. The ''[[Gyuhap Chongseo]]'', an ancient women's encyclopedia, includes various methods for making perfume.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to ''Gyuhap Chongseo'', eyebrows were the central feature of a woman's face.<ref name=\":0\" /> The work describes ten popular eyebrow shapes. Crescent or willow leaf shapes were most popular. Plant ash was the basic raw material used for eyebrow ink, with which women drew their eyebrows in various shapes. The primary colors were black, blue, and dark brown.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''Yeonji'' is the Korean name of rouge, which was used to color the lips and cheeks. It could be made from [[safflower]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the [[Joseon period]], luxurious makeup was forbidden because of Confucianism. Upper-class women tended to copy the makeup and style of [[gisaeng]] during this period.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Modern times===\n\nFollowing the [[Kanghwa Treaty|Treaty of Kanghwa]] in 1876, Korean ports opened to foreign trade and Western styles began to influence the country. New makeup styles and products became popular, stimulating Korea's cosmetics culture and enabling mass production and consumption.\n\n''Bakgabun'', which means Park's powder, was the first mass-produced cosmetics item in Korea. It was the first Korean face powder and was a bestseller from 1916 to 1930. However, because of its lead content, sales then fell rapidly and similar products were quickly launched.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs a result of the dominance of Japanese cosmetic brands, Korean cosmetics failed to develop in the 1920s. After the country was no longer under Japanese control, the [[Korean War]] that began in 1950 further disrupted the economy. Finally, around 1961, the Korean cosmetics industry began to prosper after the passage of a law banning sales of other countries' products.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Cosmetics and skincare in Korean culture==\nKorean people focus on skin care under the influence of TV programs, [[advertisements]] and tradition. Koreans highly value even, radiant skin,<ref name=\"way\">{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Sue|title=The Korean way to pretty skin|url=http://www.guampdn.com/story/life/2015/10/05/korean-skin-care/73071930/|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> and Korean women tend to vary their beauty care regimen with the season. They use different kinds of [[moisturizer]]s such as cream for tightening pores ([[BB cream]], blemish balm or beauty balm) and lotions for lightening the skin ([[CC cream]], color correction or color control).<ref name=\"way\" />\n\nKoreans generally apply makeup every day because it offers [[sunscreen|sun protection]], a major concern.<ref name=routine>{{cite news |first=Bridget |last=March |url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/beauty-hair/beauty-trends/a42942/korean-skincare-routine-explained/ |title=The Korean skincare routine, explained |newspaper=UK Cosmospolitan |date=22 June 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"bb\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw Brown|first1=Genevieve|title=Move Over BB Cream, Here Comes CC|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Travel/move-bb-cream-cc/story?id=18816958|website=abc news|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> A big focus of Korean skincare is skin lightening,<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Eric P. H. |last1=Li |author2=Hyun Jeong Min |first3=Russell W. |last3=Belk |url=http://www.acrwebsite.org/volumes/v35/naacr_vol35_273.pdf |title=Skin Lightening and Beauty in Four Asian Cultures |journal=Advances in Consumer Research |volume=35 |year=2008 |pages=444\u201349 |publisher=Association for Consumer Research, University of Minnesota Duluth }}</ref>  which is why many Korean cosmetic products have brightening properties. Skin brightening is not the same as skin bleaching, also known as [[skin whitening]], which is a reduction of [[melanin]] in the skin. Instead, skin lightening is focused on treating [[hyperpigmentation]].\n\n\nIn order to achieve a perfectly even skin tone, Korean women go so far as to perform a daily 8 to 10-step skincare routine. Traditionally, these extensive routines include [[Cosmetics|makeup remover]], double cleansing (i.e. consecutive oil and water-based cleansing), [[Exfoliation (cosmetology)|exfoliator]], [[Toner (skin care)|toner]], essence (lightweight hydrating concentrates), treatments (boosters, serums, ampules), sheet masks (thin cotton sheets doused in a liquid-based formula that claims to moisturize, brighten, and even treat fine lines), eye cream, [[moisturizer]] and [[sunscreen]].<ref name=routine/>\n\nKorean men are also interested in skincare. Some use BB or CC cream. Cosmetics manufactured specifically for men in South Korea focus on soothing the skin after daily shaving.<ref name=\"men\">{{cite web|last1=Fujita |first1=Akiko |title=South Korean Men Cosmetics-Crazed |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/lifestyle/2013/05/south-korean-men-cosmetics-crazed/|website=ABC news |date=May 2013 |accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Industry ==\nSouth Korea is home to several large cosmetic brands, many of which export their products worldwide.<ref name=\"amore\">{{cite web|last1=Chung|first1=Grace|title=How South Korea's AmorePacific Became One Of The World's Most Innovative Companies|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/gracechung/2015/08/19/how-south-koreas-amorepacific-became-one-of-the-worlds-most-innovative-companies/#f4109e689cfd|website=Forbes|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Tony\">{{cite web|title=Top cosmetics company Tony Moly goes global|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3019027|website=Korea joongang Daily|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"in-cos\">{{cite web|title=97% visitor increase makes in-cosmetics Korea a dazzling success|url=http://news.in-cosmetics.com/2016/10/97-visitor-increase-makes-in-cosmetics-korea-a-dazzling-success/|website=in-cosmetics|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> They include:\n<!-- Only for brands with their own article -->\n* [[Amorepacific Corporation|Amorepacific]], with brands including [[Laneige]], [[Etude House]], [[Innisfree (cosmetics brand)|Innisfree]], [[Sulwhasoo]] and [[Mamonde]]\n* [[LG]], with brands including [[\u012csa Knox]] and [[The Face Shop]]\n* [[Nature Republic]]\n\n== See also ==\n{{commonscat|Cosmetics in South Korea}}\n*[[Coreana Cosmetic Museum]]\n*[[K-Beauty]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n {{Authority control}}\n<!-- {{Asia topic|Cosmetics in}} -->\n\n[[Category:Cosmetics]]\n[[Category:Korean culture]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Korean cosmetics on a shelf.jpg|thumb|250px|Various Korean cosmetics products (peeling gel, essence, cleanser, toner, lotion and two types of creams) on a bathroom shelf]]\n\nKorea has an ancient history of cosmetics use, and today it is an important industry in South Korea.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Cosmetic box, stoneware with celadon glaze, Goryeo Dynasty.jpg|thumb|Goryeo Dynasty cosmetic box]]\n\n===Ancient times===\nRecords of the use of cosmetics in Korea date back to the time of the [[Three Kingdoms of Korea]], and the use of makeup flourished during the [[Goryeo kingdom]].{{cn|date=July 2017}} Cosmetics were made from lotions extracted from plants, including gourd stems; [[Mung bean|Ground mung bean]] contains [[saponin]] and was helpful for cleansing. [[Castor oil]]s and [[camellia oil]]s were used as hair oil. They had a pleasant smell and were not sticky. To moisturise and add gloss to the skin, safflower oil was used. [[Apricot]] and [[peach]] oils were used to remove freckles and liver spots. A powder called 'mibun' or 'baekbun' was made from ground rice and [[millet]] blended with water or oil.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2013/01/135_129776.html|title=Tracing history of cosmetics|website=the koreatimes|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nScents were added to extracts from grains and other plants, for example from dried clove buds. Perfume was also used to relieve stresses and tiredness. The ''[[Gyuhap Chongseo]]'', an ancient women's encyclopedia, includes various methods for making perfume.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to ''Gyuhap Chongseo'', eyebrows were the central feature of a woman's face.<ref name=\":0\" /> The work describes ten popular eyebrow shapes. Crescent or willow leaf shapes were most popular. Plant ash was the basic raw material used for eyebrow ink, with which women drew their eyebrows in various shapes. The primary colors were black, blue, and dark brown.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n''Yeonji'' is the Korean name of rouge, which was used to colour the lips and cheeks. It could be made from [[safflower]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the [[Joseon period]], luxurious makeup was forbidden because of Confucianism. Upper-class women tended to copy the makeup and style of [[gisaeng]] during this period.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Modern times===\n\nFollowing the [[Kanghwa Treaty|Treaty of Kanghwa]] in 1876, Korean ports opened to foreign trade and Western styles began to influence the country. New makeup styles and products became popular, stimulating Korea's cosmetics culture and enabling mass production and consumption.\n\n''Bakgabun'', which means Park's powder, was the first mass-produced cosmetics item in Korea. It was the first Korean face powder and was a bestseller from 1916 to 1930. However, because of its lead content, sales then fell rapidly and similar products were quickly launched.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs a result of the dominance of Japanese cosmetic brands, Korean cosmetics failed to develop in the 1920s. After the country was no longer under Japanese control, the [[Korean War]] that began in 1950 further disrupted the economy. Finally, around 1961, the Korean cosmetics industry began to prosper after the passage of a law banning sales of other countries' products.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Cosmetics and skincare in Korean culture==\nKorean people focus on skin care under the influence of TV programs, [[advertisements]] and tradition. Koreans highly value even, radiant skin,<ref name=\"way\">{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Sue|title=The Korean way to pretty skin|url=http://www.guampdn.com/story/life/2015/10/05/korean-skin-care/73071930/|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> and Korean women tend to vary their beauty care regimen with the season. They use different kinds of [[moisturizer]]s such as cream for tightening pores ([[BB cream]], blemish balm or beauty balm) and lotions for lightening the skin ([[CC cream]], colour correction or colour control).<ref name=\"way\" />\n\nKoreans generally apply makeup every day because it offers [[sunscreen|sun protection]], a major concern.<ref name=routine>{{cite news |first=Bridget |last=March |url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/uk/beauty-hair/beauty-trends/a42942/korean-skincare-routine-explained/ |title=The Korean skincare routine, explained |newspaper=UK Cosmospolitan |date=22 June 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"bb\">{{cite web|last1=Shaw Brown|first1=Genevieve|title=Move Over BB Cream, Here Comes CC|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Travel/move-bb-cream-cc/story?id=18816958|website=abc news|accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref> A big focus of Korean skincare is skin lightening,<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Eric P. H. |last1=Li |author2=Hyun Jeong Min |first3=Russell W. |last3=Belk |url=http://www.acrwebsite.org/volumes/v35/naacr_vol35_273.pdf |title=Skin Lightening and Beauty in Four Asian Cultures |journal=Advances in Consumer Research |volume=35 |year=2008 |pages=444\u201349 |publisher=Association for Consumer Research, University of Minnesota Duluth }}</ref>  which is why many Korean cosmetic products have brightening properties. Skin brightening is not the same as skin bleaching, also known as [[skin whitening]], which is a reduction of [[melanin]] in the skin. Instead, skin lightening is focused on treating [[hyperpigmentation]].\n\n\nIn order to achieve a perfectly even skin tone, Korean women go so far as to perform a daily 8 to 10-step skincare routine. Traditionally, these extensive routines include [[Cosmetics|makeup remover]], double cleansing (i.e. consecutive oil and water-based cleansing), [[Exfoliation (cosmetology)|exfoliator]], [[Toner (skin care)|toner]], essence (lightweight hydrating concentrates), treatments (boosters, serums, ampoules), sheet masks (thin cotton sheets doused in a liquid-based formula that claims to moisturize, brighten, and even treat fine lines), eye cream, [[moisturizer]] and [[sunscreen]].<ref name=routine/>\n\nKorean men are also interested in skincare. Some use BB or CC cream. Cosmetics manufactured specifically for men in South Korea focus on soothing the skin after daily shaving.<ref name=\"men\">{{cite web|last1=Fujita |first1=Akiko |title=South Korean Men Cosmetics-Crazed |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/lifestyle/2013/05/south-korean-men-cosmetics-crazed/|website=ABC news |date=May 2013 |accessdate=30 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Industry ==\nSouth Korea is home to several large cosmetic brands, many of which export their products worldwide.<ref name=\"amore\">{{cite web|last1=Chung|first1=Grace|title=How South Korea's AmorePacific Became One Of The World's Most Innovative Companies|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/gracechung/2015/08/19/how-south-koreas-amorepacific-became-one-of-the-worlds-most-innovative-companies/#f4109e689cfd|website=Forbes|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Tony\">{{cite web|title=Top cosmetics company Tony Moly goes global|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3019027|website=Korea joongang Daily|accessdate=22 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"in-cos\">{{cite web|title=97% visitor increase makes in-cosmetics Korea a dazzling success|url=http://news.in-cosmetics.com/2016/10/97-visitor-increase-makes-in-cosmetics-korea-a-dazzling-success/|website=in-cosmetics|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> They include:\n<!-- Only for brands with their own article -->\n* [[Amorepacific Corporation|Amorepacific]], with brands including [[Laneige]], [[Etude House]], [[Innisfree (cosmetics brand)|Innisfree]], [[Sulwhasoo]] and [[Mamonde]]\n* [[LG]], with brands including [[\u012csa Knox]] and [[The Face Shop]]\n* [[Nature Republic]]\n\n== See also ==\n{{commonscat|Cosmetics in South Korea}}\n*[[Coreana Cosmetic Museum]]\n*[[K-Beauty]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n {{Authority control}}\n<!-- {{Asia topic|Cosmetics in}} -->\n\n[[Category:Cosmetics]]\n[[Category:Korean culture]]\n", "name_user": "Tanishka017", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosmetics_in_Korea"}
{"title_page": "Symon Sadik", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Symon Sadik\n| image              = Symon Sadik (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Symon in 2018\n| other_names        = Gentle Star\n| birth_date         = 30 August 1985\n(Age 34 years)\n| birth_place        = Kalapara, [[Kishoreganj]], [[Bangladesh]]\n| education          = [[Kishoregonj Government Boys' High School]]\n| occupation         = \u2022 [[Film Actor]]\n\u2022 [[Model (person)|Model]]\n\u2022 [[Politician]]\n\u2022 [[Assistant director]]\n| yearsactive        = 2012\u2013present\n| notable_works      = \u2022 [[Ji Hujur]] \n\u2022 [[PoraMon]]\n\u2022 Er Beshi Valobasha Jay Na\n\u2022 Tomar kache Rini \n\u2022 Chupi Chupi Prem\n\u2022 [[Black Money]] \n\u2022 Mayabini\n\u2022 Tui Amar \n\u2022 [[Jannat (2018 film)]]\n| style              = \u2022 [[Romance film|Romantic]]\n\u2022 [[Comedy]]\n\u2022 [[Action film|Action]]\n\u2022 [[Drama]]\n| height             = 1.73 m\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Deepa Sadik|2014}}\n| partner            = Mohammed Sadikur Rahman, Umme Kulsum\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = \u2022 Bioscope Borsho-Sera Awards in (2013)\n\n\u2022 [[Babisas Award]] for Featured Actor Male in (2016)\n\n\u2022 [[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor]] (2018)\n\u2022 AJFB Star Award in (2018 & 2019)\n| nationality        = [[Bangladeshi]]\n}}  \n\n'''Symon Sadik''' is a Bangladeshi film Actor Known for his Works in [[Dhallywood|Dhallywood Cinema]]. And He was an [[assistant director|Assistant Director]] and worked with [[Zakir Hossain Raju]]. He made his debut as a lead in the 2012 Bangladeshi film ''[[Ji Hujur]], Directed by [[Zakir Hossain Raju]], And opposite [[Sara Zerin]]. And his second film [[PoraMon]], Directed by [[Zakir Hossain Raju]] and opposite [[Mahiya Mahi]]. And he won Bioscope Borsho-Sera Awards for Best acting in [[PoraMon]].'' And He also won [[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor]] for his role in the film ''[[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]]'' (2018).\n\n==Career==\n[[Symon Sadik]] was born on August 30, 1985, at Kalapara, Kishoreganj, Bangladesh. He rose up in the Kishoreganj Sadar. [[Symon Sadik|Symon]] passed SSC from Kishoreganj Govt. Boys School. He was so much passionate about media arena from early childhood and eventually participated in the Super Hero and Heroin competition organized by NTV.\n\n[[Symon Sadik]] and [[Sara Zerin]]  started in 2012 with director Zakir Hossain Raju in [[Ji Hujur|Ji Huzur]] movie. Later, he was introduced to the audience by starring in the successful movie [[PoraMon]] in (2013). [[Symon Sadik]] got his breakthrough in the film [[PoraMon]]. And he also acted in Bangladeshi film Er beshi Valobasha Jay Na (2013), Tui Shudhu Amar, Tomar Kache Rini, 16 Ana Prem, Shopno Chowa in (2014), Chupi Chupi Prem, Black money, Action Jasmine in (2015),Chokher Dekha, Pure Jay Mon, Matir Pori, Ojante Valobasha in (2016), Mayabini, Khash Zamin, Tui Amar in (2017), And He was acted opposite [[Mahiya Mahi]] in the [[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]] film on 2018. He was awarded the [[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor]] in the category for his outstanding performance in the film [[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]] and he also acted in \"Matal\" movie in (2018)   \n\nAnd  His upcoming movies is [[Ananda Ashru|Ananda Ashro]] (2020) Directed by [[Mostafizur Rahman Manik]] with same team of successful movie [[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat (2018)]], There was a movie made under the same name [[Anondo Osru|Anondo osru]] in (1997) starring [[Salman Shah (actor)|Salman Shah]] and [[Shabnur]], But there is no similarity in the story of these two films.   \n\nAnd Nodir Buke Chand with opposite [[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]] and Amar Ma Amar Beheshto in (2020)   \n\n==Filmography & Awards  ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Key\n|{{Not yet}}{{Dagger}}\n|Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Director\n!Co-Star\n!Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |2012\n![[Ji Hujur]]\n|Abdur Rahman \n|[[Zakir Hossain Raju|Jakir Hossain raju]] \n|[[Sara Zerin]]/ [[Kazi Hayat]]/ [[Chikon Ali]]\n|Debut Film \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n![[PoraMon]]\n|Sujon\n|[[Zakir Hossain Raju|Jakir Hossain raju]] \n|[[Mahiya Mahi]]\n|Nominated: Bioscope Borsho-sera awards and\n\nThe film is remake of Tamil movie [[Mynaa]]\n|-\n!Er Beshi Valobasha Jay Na \n|Robi\n|[[Zakir Hossain Raju|Jakir Hossain raju]] \n|[[Nijhum Rubina|Nijhum Robina]] / Mukta / Bipasha / Sohel khan\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" |2014\n!Tui Shudhu Amar  \n|Shuvo\n|Raju Chowdhury \n|Moumita mou/ Sinthiya/ [[Kazi Hayat]]/ [[Chikon Ali]]/ Alexander Bo\n|\n|-\n!Dhonsho Manab\n|\n|Mizanur Rahman Shamim\n|Eshita / Rubel / Alexander Bo\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Tomar Kache Rini \n|Raju \n|[[Shahadat Hussain|Shahadat Hossain]]\n|[[Toma Mirza]]/ [[Farida Akhtar Babita|Bobita]]/ [[Prabir Mitra|Probir Mitra]]/ Shahid khan/ Shahrukh khan / Rehana jolly\n|\n|-\n!Swapno Chowa\n|Shakti\n|Shafiq Hasan \n|[[Bobby (actress)|Eamin Haque Bobby]] / [[Kazi Hayat]] / [[Misha Sawdagor]]\n|\n|-\n!Rana Plaza \n|\n|Nuzrul Islam khan\n|[[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]] \n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Mayamoy\n|\n|P A kajol \n|\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!16 Ana Prem \n|Amit\n|Ali Azad \n|Tania/ [[Kazi Hayat]]/ [[Chikon Ali]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"13\" |2015\n!Chupi Chupi Prem \n|RRR\n|[[Mostafizur Rahman Manik]] \n|Priyoti/ [[Ali Raj]]/ [[Misha Sawdagor|Misha Showdagor]]\n|\n|-\n!Surprise \n|\n|F I Manik \n|[[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]]\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Probashi Don \n|\n|Shahin Suman \n|[[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]] \n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Action Jasmine \n|Inspector Akash \n|[[Iftakar Chowdhury]] \n|[[Bobby (actress)|Eamin Haque Bobby]] \n|The film is remake of Telugu movie ''[[Vikramarkudu]]''\n|-\n!Bhulte Parina Tare\n|\n|\n|\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Moner Moddhe Lekha\n|\n|\n|\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Follow Me \n|\n|\n|\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Mon Shudhu Tumari \n|\n|Shahin Suman \n|[[Keya (actress)|Keya]]\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Prem Bole Kichu Nei\n|\n|[[Mostafizur Rahman Manik]] \n|\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Mon Jole\n|\n|Devashish Biswas \n|\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Black Money \n|Srabon\n|[[Shafi Uddin Shafi]] \n|[[Moushumi Hamid]]/ [[Keya (actress)|Keya]]\n|The Film is Remake of Telugu Movie [[Paisa (film)|Paisa]].\n|-\n!Shomoshamoyik\n|\n|\n|\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Tomar Jonno Mon Kandey\n|\n|A J Rana \n|[[Sara Zerin]]/ [[Ali Raj]]\n|Unreleased \n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2016\n!Chokher Dekha \n|Sadmaan\n|P A Kojol \n|[[Ahona Rahman]]/ [[Kazi Hayat]]\n|\n|-\n!Matir Pori \n|Shuvo\n|Saimon Tareq\n|Sadia Islam Lamia \n|\n|-\n!Gopon Shonket\n|\n|Tajul Islam\n|Alvira Imu/ Moumita Mou/ [[Amit Hasan]]/ Rehana joll\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Pure Jay Mon \n|Surjo\n|Apurba Rana \n|[[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]] / [[Ali Raj]]\n|\n|-\n!Ojante Valobasha \n|Prem\n|A J Rana \n|[[Alisha Pradhan]] / Ena / Shakil Raj\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2017\n!Bahaduri \n|\n|Shafiq Hasan \n|[[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]]/[[Zayed Khan (Bangladeshi actor)|Zayed Khan]]/ [[Misha Sawdagor]]\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Mayabiny \n|Prem \n|Akash Charjee\n|[[Airin Sultana]]/[[Kazi Hayat]] /[[Amit Hasan|Amit hasan]]\n|''The Film is Remake of Tamil Movie''\n\n''[[Muni 2: Kanchana]]''\n|-\n!Khash Zamin \n|Robi\n|Sarwar Hossain \n|Bipasha Kabir / [[Kazi Hayat]]\n|\n|-\n!Jol Shewla \n|\n|Jasmine Aktar Nodi\n|Prokrity \n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Tui Amar \n|[[Symon Sadik|Symon]] \n|Sajol Ahmad \n|[[Misty Jannat|Misty Zannat]] / [[Ali Raj]] /[[Chikon Ali]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n![[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]]\n|Aslam / Iftikhar \n|[[Mostafizur Rahman Manik]] \n|[[Mahiya Mahi]] / [[Ali Raj]] / [[Misha Sawdagor]]\n|[[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor]] and\n[[Jannat (2018 film)|AJFB Star Awards]] \n|-\n!Matal\n|Rana\n|Shahin Suman \n|[[Adhora Khan|Adhora khan]]/[[Misha Sawdagor]]/ Shipon Mitra\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2019\n!Jibon Theke Pawa \n|Joy\n|Saidur Rahman Sajol  \n|[[Mahiya Mahi]] \n|[[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman|The father of the nation is a ('''Short''' '''Film''