Prem\n|A J Rana \n|[[Alisha Pradhan]] / Ena / Shakil Raj\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2017\n!Bahaduri \n|\n|Shafiq Hasan \n|[[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]]/[[Zayed Khan (Bangladeshi actor)|Zayed Khan]]/ [[Misha Sawdagor]]\n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Mayabiny \n|Prem \n|Akash Charjee\n|[[Airin Sultana]]/[[Kazi Hayat]] /[[Amit Hasan|Amit hasan]]\n|''The Film is Remake of Tamil Movie''\n\n''[[Muni 2: Kanchana]]''\n|-\n!Khash Zamin \n|Robi\n|Sarwar Hossain \n|Bipasha Kabir / [[Kazi Hayat]]\n|\n|-\n!Jol Shewla \n|\n|Jasmine Aktar Nodi\n|Prokrity \n|Unreleased \n|-\n!Tui Amar \n|[[Symon Sadik|Symon]] \n|Sajol Ahmad \n|[[Misty Jannat|Misty Zannat]] / [[Ali Raj]] /[[Chikon Ali]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n![[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]]\n|Aslam / Iftikhar \n|[[Mostafizur Rahman Manik]] \n|[[Mahiya Mahi]] / [[Ali Raj]] / [[Misha Sawdagor]]\n|[[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor]] and\n[[Jannat (2018 film)|AJFB Star Awards]] \n|-\n!Matal\n|Rana\n|Shahin Suman \n|[[Adhora Khan|Adhora khan]]/[[Misha Sawdagor]]/ Shipon Mitra\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2019\n!Jibon Theke Pawa \n|Joy\n|Saidur Rahman Sajol  \n|[[Mahiya Mahi]] \n|[[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman|The father of the nation is a ('''Short''' '''Film''') about the dreams and ideals of Bangabandhu]].\n|-\n!Opare Chondraboti{{Dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n|\n|Rafiq Shikdar\n|[[Apu Biswas]]\n|Unreleased\n|-\n![[Eto Prem Eto Maya]]{{Dagger}}\n|\n|[[Mostafizur Rahman Manik]] \n|\n|Unreleased \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2020\n![[Ananda Ashru|Ananda Ashro]]{{Dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n|Farhad\n|[[Mostafizur Rahman Manik]] \n|[[Mahiya Mahi]]/ [[Ali Raj]]/ Joy Chowdhury\n|Shooting also complete \n|-\n![[Nodir Buke Chand]]{{Dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n|Chand\n|Shaikot Hasan \n|[[Pori Moni|PoriMoni]]/ [[Omar Sani]]/ [[Aruna Biswas]]\n|Filming \n|-\n![[Amar Ma Amar Beheshto]]{{Dagger|alt=}}\n|\n|[[Badiul Alam Khokon|Bodiul Alam Khokon]]\n|[[Mahiya Mahi]]/ [[Shuchorita]]/ [[Ali Raj]]/ [[Misha Sawdagor]]\n|Filming \n|-\n|2021\n!#GSSS41{{Dagger}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n\n\n'''Awards'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Film\n!Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[PoraMon|Bioscope Borsho - Shera Awards]] \n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|Best Film Actor]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[PoraMon]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Nominated \n|-\n|Best Couple with ([[Mahiya Mahi]]) \n|-\n|2016\n|[[Babisas Award|Babisas Award for Featured Actor Male]]\n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|Best Film actor]] \n|_\n|Nominated\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2018\n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|AJFB Star Awards]] \n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|Best Film Actor]] \n|_\n|Nominated \n|-\n|[[43rd Bangladesh National Film Awards]]\n|[[Symon Sadik|Best Film Actor]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Jannat (2018 film)|Jannat]]\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Symon Sadik|AJFB Star Awards]]  \n|[[List of Bangladeshi actors|Best Film Actor]]\n|Nominated \n|}\n\n\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n# [[PoraMon|\"\u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u09a6\u09bf\u0995 \u09aa\u09cb\u09a1\u09bc\u09be\u09ae\u09a8 (\u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09e9) \u099c\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09b0 \u09b9\u09cb\u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09a8 \u09b0\u09be\u099c\u09c1 \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u099a\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09a4 \u09b8\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09ae\u09be\u09a7\u09cd\u09af\u09ae\u09c7 \u099c\u09a8\u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09af\u09bc\u09a4\u09be \u09b2\u09be\u09ad \u0995\u09b0\u09c7\"]]\n#[[PoraMon|\u09a6\u09b0\u09cd\u09b6\u0995 \u09ad\u09cb\u099f\u09c7 \"\u09ac\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09cb\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09cb\u09aa \u09ac\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09b8\u09c7\u09b0\u09be\" \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09e9 \u09b9\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u099b\u09c7\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u09a6\u09bf\u0995]] \n#\"Symon Sadik Won, [[Babisas Award]] for Featured Actor Male in (2016)\".\n#[[Bobby (actress)|\"\u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u09ac\u09ac\u09bf\u09b0 \u099c\u09c1\u099f\u09bf, \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09aa\u09cd\u09a8 \u099b\u09cb\u0981\u09af\u09bc\u09be \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u0985\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u0995\u09b6\u09a8 \u099c\u09c7\u09b8\u09ae\u09bf\u09a8\"]]\n#[[Moushumi Hamid|\"\u09ae\u09cc\u09b8\u09c1\u09ae\u09c0 \u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09bf\u09a6 \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \"Black Money\" \u09ae\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf \u09aa\u09c7\u09b2\"]] \n#[[Airin Sultana|\"Horror and Comedy movie \"Mayabiny\" in (2017) Airin sultana with Symon Sadik\"]]\n#[[Misty Jannat|\"\"\u09ae\u09bf\u09b7\u09cd\u099f\u09bf \u099c\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be\u09a4 \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u09a6\u09bf\u0995 (\u09a4\u09c1\u0987 \u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0) \u09b8\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be\u09a4\u09c7\"\"]]\n#[[Jannat (2018 film)|\"\u0986\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cb \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09ae\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09b0 \u099c\u09c1\u099f\u09bf, \u09ae\u09cb\u09b8\u09cd\u09a4\u09be\u09ab\u09bf\u099c\u09c1\u09b0 \u09b0\u09b9\u09ae\u09be\u09a8 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u099a\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u09a4 (\u099c\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09a8\u09be\u09a4 \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09ee) \u09b8\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be\u09a4\u09c7\"]]\n#[[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Actor|\"\"\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u099a\u09b2\u099a\u09cd\u099a\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0 \u09aa\u09c1\u09b0\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09be\u09b0 \u09aa\u09c7\u09b2\u09c7\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u09b8\u09be\u09a6\u09bf\u0995 \"\"]]\n#[[Adhora Khan|\"\"\u0985\u09a7\u09b0\u09be \u098f\u09ac\u0982 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 (\u09ae\u09be\u09a4\u09be\u09b2) \u09b8\u09bf\u09a8\u09c7\u09ae\u09be \u09ae\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf \u09aa\u09c7\u09b2 \"\"]] \n#\"\u09ae\u09c1\u0995\u09cd\u09a4\u09bf \u09aa\u09c7\u09b2 \u09b8\u09be\u0987\u09ae\u09a8 \u0985\u09a7\u09b0\u09be\u09b0 '\u09ae\u09be\u09a4\u09be\u09b2\". ''Janakantha'' (in Bengali). 27 October 2018. Retrieved 28 July 2019.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|6084492}}\n{{Bangladesh National Film Award Best Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control|Awards and Nominate=}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadik, Symon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kishoreganj District]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male film actors]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Film Awards (Bangladesh)]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n\n\n{{Bangladesh-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sohail ariyan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symon_Sadik"}
{"title_page": "Bed\u0159ich Homola", "text_new": "{{dablinks|date=April 2020}}\nArmy General '''Bed\u0159ich Homola''' (June 2, 1887 [[B\u011ble\u010d]]  - January 5, 1943 [[Berlin]], [[Pl\u00f6tzensee Prison]]) was a [[Czechoslovak]] soldier, general, legionnaire, and provincial commander of the national defense during the [[Nazi]] occupation of [[Bohemia]] and [[Moravia]]. He used the code name ''Ataman''.<ref> Kniha narozynech; Liten 24; [https://ebadatelna.soapraha.cz/d/7945/171]</ref>\n\n==Youth==\nHe was born on June 2, 1887, in B\u011ble\u010d, near [[Zadn\u00ed T\u0159eba\u0148]], to V\u00e1clav and Marie Homol, who were peasants. After completing elementary school in [[Lithuania]] in 1899 he attended secondary school in [[Hostomice]], transferring in 1901 to a German-language school in [[B\u00edlina]]. From 1903 to 1907 he attended the College of Civil Engineering in [[Prague]].<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nIn 1907\u201308 he was employed by the Prague architect [[Zuslicht]]. In 1908\u201309 he did volunteer work in Prague; in 1909\u201310 he worked for a construction company in [[Serbia]] and from 1910 to 1914 he had a job at the Prague City Hall.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===World War One===\n====Austrian Army====\nHomola joined the [[Austrian army]] as part of the mobilization of July 27, 1914. As a member of the 88th Infantry Regiment, he went to the [[Russian front]], where he was injured in September and returned home. A year later, now holding the rank of Lieutenant, he returned to the front at [[Debrecen]] and [[Galicia]]. On September 14, 1915, he was wounded again and captured by the Russians, who took him to [[Moscow]].<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\n====Czechoslovak legions in Russia====\nHomola joined the [[Czechoslovak Legion|Czechoslovak legions in Russia]] on February 15, 1916. He served as a company commander, then as the enlisted school commander. He went on to become commander of the section \u010cenokovka - Do\u010d at Bachma\u010de and then commander of the [[Northern Front]]. Beginning on May 25, he commanded a staff train and participated in the fighting at [[Marjanovky]]. On October 27, 1918, having been promoted to the rank of Major, he was appointed deputy commander of the officer school. On July 20, 2019, he became inspector of divisional courses for non-commissioned officers.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nOn September 29, 1919, he married Galina Fadd\u011bjev, with whom he had a son, Oleg Homola (1921\u20132001), who would grow up to become a [[Communist Party]] politician and a literary scholar. On April 22, 1920, he set off on a trip to [[Vladivostok]], returning to his homeland via [[Singapore]], [[Suez]], and [[Trieste]].<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\n===First and Second Republics===\nIn 1921-22 he attended the war school in Prague. He was promoted to the rank of Lieutenant Colonel on September 20, 1922, and was appointed deputy commander of the military academy in Hranice na Morav\u011b. After the suicides of two academy students, one of them the son of the Artillery Commander of the 1st Division of the Czechoslovak Legions in Russia, drew media attention to the strict regime Homola had established at the academy, he was transferred to the Staff 7 Infantry Division in Olomouc, where he served as commander. On January 10, 1925, he was promoted to Colonel and beginning on October 1, 1925, he was commander of the 27th Regiment in Olomouc.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 1927, he was appointed interim commander, and on March 31 commander, of the 14th Infantry Brigade in [[Kromeriz]]. On February 21, 1929, he was promoted to the rank of Brigadier General. On March 5 he became commander of the 1st Infantry Division and garrison commander of Prague. On July 1, 1935, he became commander of the VII Army Corps with the rank of Divisional General. He participated in both of the mobilizations in 1938, in May and September. From March 9 to 11, 1939, at the behest of the government, he disarmed the [[Hlinka]] Guards and had their leaders interned. This event was later known in [[Slovakia]] as \u201cHomol's coup.\u201d<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nOn March 14, 1939, he was called back to Prague without being told any reason. Unable to cross the newly established national border by car, he continued on by foot through the Beskydy Mountains while his wife was being interned by Hlinka Guardsmen in [[Turzovka]]. He managed to reach Moravia, where he met the advancing [[Wehrmacht]]. On March 19, 1939, a Slovak newspaper incorrectly reported that he had been shot and killed at the border. At the end of March 1939, he appeared in Prague with his wife (who had been released from captivity) and the two of them settled in Prague-Dejvice. He then began to work intensively with other officers of the now-defunct Czechoslovak Army to build a military resistance organization. Once the Defense of the Nation was formed, the Great Command of Prague was placed in his hands.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nIn August he went into hiding near the town hall in [[Sk\u0159e\u017e]]. In January 1940 he participated in the establishment of the ''HOME''. In February 1940, after the arrest of generals [[Joseph White]] and [[Hugo Vojta]], he became commander of the Defense of the Nation. From his office he tried to unite the military and political resistance against the occupiers under a single organization, namely ''Introduction''. After the defeat of [[France]], he tried to orient the domestic resistance to the [[USSR]] and opposed (together with [[Josef Balab\u00e1n]]) Bene\u0161's fears of the \"[[Soviet]]ization of Czechoslovakia\" by saying that \"there will be no communism in 30-50 years, but there will be a nation.\u201d In addition, he maintained that after liberation, the rise of the extreme left and right could be prevented by a strong government.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nIn October 1940 he escaped arrest by the [[Gestapo]] and was forced to move to a new hiding place, where he continued to plan for an anti-German uprising by forces that would retake the parts of Czechoslovakia that had been invaded by the Nazis. Since his plans would require Allied air support and a decline in Nazi power, many of his colleagues opposed them. After the Nazis placed [[Reinhard Heydrich]] in charge of the former Czechoslovak state on September 27, 1941, a state of emergency was declared and extensive arrests and executions took place. On October 25, 1941, Homola admitted to his Allied contacts in [[London]] that all of his work to establish a resistance had been undone.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\n===Arrest and execution===\nHe was arrested on December 31, 1941, at the corner of [[King George Square]] and Vinohradsk\u00e1 Street in Prague. He was incarcerated in the Pankr\u00e1c prison, from which he was transported for questioning in [[Pecek Palace]]. In September 1942 he was taken to [[Dresden]] and from there to Pl\u00f6tzensee Berlin Prison, where he was sentenced to death for high treason. During his last days in captivity he conducted himself with courage. He was executed on January 5, 1943.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; VHU; [http://www.vhu.cz/bedrich-homola/ ]</ref>\n\nIn October 1946 he was promoted posthumously to General of the Army, effective October 1942.\n\n==Orders and decorations==\n*\u0158\u00e1d sv. Anny II. class with swords (1919)\n*Czechoslovak War Cross 1914-1918 \n*The Order of M. R. Stefanik \"Sokol\" for valor (September 17, 1919) \n*Czechoslovak Victory medal\n*War Cross with Palm Tree (France, November 1928) during the fighting in Siberia\n*Officer of the Legion of Honor (France, October 7, 1931)\n*\u0160tef\u00e1nik's commemorative badge of the first degree (Czechoslovakia, September 27, 1945)\n*Czechoslovak War Cross 1939<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; VHU; [http://www.vhu.cz/bedrich-homola/ ]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{dablinks|date=April 2020}}\nArmy General '''Bed\u0159ich Homola''' (June 2, 1887 [[B\u011ble\u010d]]  - January 5, 1943 [[Berlin]], [[Pl\u00f6tzensee Prison]]) was a [[Czechoslovak]] soldier, general, legionnaire, and provincial commander of the national defense during the [[Nazi]] occupation of [[Bohemia]] and [[Moravia]]. He used the code name ''Ataman''.<ref> Kniha narozynech; Liten 24; [https://ebadatelna.soapraha.cz/d/7945/171]</ref>\n\n==Youth==\nHe was born on June 2, 1887, in B\u011ble\u010d, near [[Zadn\u00ed T\u0159eba\u0148]], to V\u00e1clav and Marie Homol, who were peasants. After completing elementary school in [[Lithuania]] in 1899 he attended secondary school in [[Hostomice]], transferring in 1901 to a German-language school in [[B\u00edlina]]. From 1903 to 1907 he attended the College of Civil Engineering in [[Prague]].<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nIn 1907\u201308 he was employed by the Prague architect [[Zuslicht]]. In 1908\u201309 he did volunteer work in Prague; in 1909\u201310 he worked for a construction company in [[Serbia]] and from 1910 to 1914 he had a job at the Prague City Hall.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===World War One===\n====Austrian Army====\nHomola joined the [[Austrian army]] as part of the mobilization of July 27, 1914. As a member of the 88th Infantry Regiment, he went to the [[Russian front]], where he was injured in September and returned home. A year later, now holding the rank of Lieutenant, he returned to the front at [[Debrecen]] and [[Galicia]]. On September 14, 1915, he was wounded again and captured by the Russians, who took him to [[Moscow]].<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\n====Czechoslovak legions in Russia====\nHomola joined the [[Czechoslovak Legion|Czechoslovak legions in Russia]] on February 15, 1916. He served as a company commander, then as the enlisted school commander. He went on to become commander of the section \u010cenokovka - Do\u010d at Bachma\u010de and then commander of the [[Northern Front]]. Beginning on May 25, he commanded a staff train and participated in the fighting at [[Marjanovky]]. On October 27, 1918, having been promoted to the rank of Major, he was appointed deputy commander of the officer school. On July 20, 2019, he became inspector of divisional courses for non-commissioned officers.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nOn September 29, 1919, he married Galina Fadd\u011bjev, with whom he had a son, Oleg Homola (1921\u20132001), who would grow up to become a [[Communist Party]] politician and a literary scholar. On April 22, 1920, he set off on a trip to [[Vladivostok]], returning to his homeland via [[Singapore]], [[Suez]], and [[Trieste]].<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\n===First and Second Republics===\nIn 1921-22 he attended the war school in Prague. He was promoted to the rank of Lieutenant Colonel on September 20, 1922, and was appointed deputy commander of the military academy in Hranice na Morav\u011b. After the suicides of two academy students, one of them the son of a the Artillery Commander of the 1st Division of the Czechoslovak Legions in Russia, drew media attention to the strict regime Homola had established at the academy, he was transferred to the Staff 7 Infantry Division in Olomouc, where he served as commander. On January 10, 1925, he was promoted to Colonel and beginning on October 1, 1925, he was commander of the 27th Regiment in Olomouc.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 1927, he was appointed interim commander, and on March 31 commander, of the 14th Infantry Brigade in [[Kromeriz]]. On February 21, 1929, he was promoted to the rank of Brigadier General. On March 5 he became commander of the 1st Infantry Division and garrison commander of Prague. On July 1, 1935, he became commander of the VII Army Corps with the rank of Divisional General. He participated in both of the mobilizations in 1938, in May and September. From March 9 to 11, 1939, at the behest of the government, he disarmed the [[Hlinka]] Guards and had their leaders interned. This event was later known in [[Slovakia]] as \u201cHomol's coup.\u201d<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nOn March 14, 1939, he was called back to Prague without being told any reason. Unable to cross the newly established national border by car, he continued on by foot through the Beskydy Mountains while his wife was being interned by Hlinka Guardsmen in [[Turzovka]]. He managed to reach Moravia, where he met the advancing [[Wehrmacht]]. On March 19, 1939, a Slovak newspaper incorrectly reported that he had been shot and killed at the border. At the end of March 1939, he appeared in Prague with his wife (who had been released from captivity) and the two of them settled in Prague-Dejvice. He then began to work intensively with other officers of the now-defunct Czechoslovak Army to build a military resistance organization. Once the Defense of the Nation was formed, the Great Command of Prague was placed in his hands.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nIn August he went into hiding near the town hall in [[Sk\u0159e\u017e]]. In January 1940 he participated in the establishment of the ''HOME''. In February 1940, after the arrest of generals [[Joseph White]] and [[Hugo Vojta]], he became commander of the Defense of the Nation. From his office he tried to unite the military and political resistance against the occupiers under a single organization, namely ''Introduction''. After the defeat of [[France]], he tried to orient the domestic resistance to the [[USSR]] and opposed (together with [[Josef Balab\u00e1n]]) Bene\u0161's fears of the \"[[Soviet]]ization of Czechoslovakia\" by saying that \"there will be no communism in 30-50 years, but there will be a nation.\u201d In addition, he maintained that after liberation, the rise of the extreme left and right could be prevented by a strong government.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\nIn October 1940 he escaped arrest by the [[Gestapo]] and was forced to move to a new hiding place, where he continued to plan for an anti-German uprising by forces that would retake the parts of Czechoslovakia that had been invaded by the Nazis. Since his plans would require Allied air support and a decline in Nazi power, many of his colleagues opposed them. After the Nazis placed [[Reinhard Heydrich]] in charge of the former Czechoslovak state on September 27, 1941, a state of emergency was declared and extensive arrests and executions took place. On October 25, 1941, Homola admitted to his Allied contacts in [[London]] that all of his work to establish a resistance had been undone.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; Zhola; [http://zhola.com/BedrichHomola/index.php?rowid=24]</ref>\n\n===Arrest and execution===\nHe was arrested on December 31, 1941, at the corner of [[King George Square]] and Vinohradsk\u00e1 Street in Prague. He was incarcerated in the Pankr\u00e1c prison, from which he was transported for questioning in [[Pecek Palace]]. In September 1942 he was taken to [[Dresden]] and from there to Pl\u00f6tzensee Berlin Prison, where he was sentenced to death for high treason. During his last days in captivity he conducted himself with courage. He was executed on January 5, 1943.<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; VHU; [http://www.vhu.cz/bedrich-homola/ ]</ref>\n\nIn October 1946 he was promoted posthumously to General of the Army, effective October 1942.\n\n==Orders and decorations==\n*\u0158\u00e1d sv. Anny II. class with swords (1919)\n*Czechoslovak War Cross 1914-1918 \n*The Order of M. R. Stefanik \"Sokol\" for valor (September 17, 1919) \n*Czechoslovak Victory medal\n*War Cross with Palm Tree (France, November 1928) during the fighting in Siberia\n*Officer of the Legion of Honor (France, October 7, 1931)\n*\u0160tef\u00e1nik's commemorative badge of the first degree (Czechoslovakia, September 27, 1945)\n*Czechoslovak War Cross 1939<ref> Bed\u0159ich Homola; VHU; [http://www.vhu.cz/bedrich-homola/ ]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stray word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bed%C5%99ich_Homola"}
