 2019}}</ref>\n* Most passing touchdowns in a game: 5 (tied with [[Joe Flacco]] and [[Tony Banks (American football)|Tony Banks]])<ref name=super8/>\n* Most games with 5 passing touchdowns: 3<ref name=super8/>\n* Most touchdown passes in the first (n) games of a season (all 2019): \n** First game: 5\n** First 2 games: 7 \n** First 3 games: 7 (tied with [[Joe Flacco]])\n** First 4 games: 10\n** First 5 games: 11\n** First 11 games: 24 (tied with [[Vinny Testaverde]])\n** First 12 games: 25\n** First 13 games: 28\n** First 14 games: 33\n** First 15 games: 36\n* Highest completion percentage in a game: 88.2<ref name=super8/>\n* Highest completion percentage in a season: 66.1 (2019)<ref>{{cite web |title=Baltimore Ravens Single-Season Passing Leaders |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/rav/single-season-passing.htm |website=pro-football-reference.com |publisher=Pro Football Reference |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n* Highest passer rating in a season: 113.3 (2019)<ref name=8Lamar/>\n* Highest touchdown/pass percentage in a season; 9% (2019)<ref name=8Lamar/>\n\n==Popular culture==\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| width  = 300px\n| video1 =[https://www.baltimoreravens.com/video/final-drive-here-s-a-teaser-of-lamar-jackson-on-celebrity-family-feud-x1092 Lamar Jackson on Celebrity Family Feud], Baltimore Ravens video\n}}\nPrior to the start of the 2019 NFL season, Jackson appeared on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Celebrity Family Feud]]'', pitting current NFL players against former NFL players.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/bs-sp-ravens-lamar-jackson-family-feud-20190226-story.html |title=Ravens quarterback Lamar Jackson to appear on 'Celebrity Family Feud' |last=Shaffer |first=Jonas |date=February 26, 2019 |website=[[Baltimore Sun]] |access-date=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/the-caw-recapping-lamar-jackson-s-performance-on-celebrity-family-feud |title=The Caw: Recapping Lamar Jackson's Performance on 'Celebrity Family Feud' |last=Mink |first=Ryan |date=July 15, 2019 |website=baltimoreravens.com |publisher=Baltimore Ravens |access-date=November 27, 2019}}</ref> Jackson's athletic abilities were featured in [[GEICO]] and [[Pizza Hut]] commercials which aired during the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ispot.tv/ad/ZnJO/pizza-hut-hut-of-the-week-ravens-v-texans |title=Pizza Hut TV Commercial, 'Hut of the Week: Ravens v. Texans' |website=iSpot.tv |publisher=2019 iSpot.tv, Inc |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ispot.tv/ad/ZABT/geico-play-of-the-day-lamar-jackson |title=GEICO TV Commercial, 'Play of the Day: Lamar Jackson |website=iSpot.tv |publisher=2019 iSpot.tv, Inc. |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tvcommercialad.com/watch/4pIeCrlQEOxHl9O |title=GEICO Play of the Day |website=tvcommercialad.com |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> During week 12 of the 2019 NFL season, the makers of ''[[Madden NFL]]'', a video game series that has sold more than 130 million copies, announced that Jackson's character speed would be upgraded from 94 to 96, making Jackson the fastest quarterback in that game's history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/11/27/madden-20-lamar-jackson-surpasses-michael-vick-fastest-quarterback/4317001002/ |title=Ravens' Lamar Jackson surpasses Michael Vick as fastest QB in Madden history |last=Reyes |first=Lorenzo |date=November 27, 2019 |website=usatoday.com |publisher=USA Today |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/11/27/lamar-jackson-passes-michael-vick-as-fastest-madden-quarterback |title=Lamar Jackson Passes Michael Vick as Fastest QB in Madden History |last=Schapiro |first=Michael |date=November 26, 2019 |website=si.com |publisher=Sports Illustrated |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> In 2018, Jackson announced the launch of his sportswear line, \"Era 8 Apparel\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pennlive.com/baltimore-ravens/2019/11/nike-under-armour-as-ravens-qb-lamar-jacksons-star-rises-marketers-wonder-if-and-where-hell-sign.html |title=Nike? Under Armour? As Ravens QB Lamar Jackson\u2019s star rises, marketers wonder if and where he\u2019ll sign |date=November 25, 2019 |website=pennlive.com |publisher=PA Media group |access-date=November 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ftp.ravenspr.com/bio_updates_player/jackson_lamar.pdf |title=8 Lamar Jackson |website=baltimoreravens.com |publisher=Baltimore Ravens |access-date=November 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Cyber Monday]] 2019, major sportswear retailer [[Fanatics (sports retailer)|Fanatics]] announced that its Lamar Jackson sportswear outsold every other professional athlete's sportswear.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/lamar-jackson-merchandise-reportedly-outsells-all-athletes-on-cyber-monday-but-tom-brady-jerseys-still-reign/ |title=Lamar Jackson merchandise reportedly outsells all athletes on Cyber Monday, but Tom Brady jerseys still reign |last=DeArdo |first=Bryan |date=December 4, 2019 |website=cbssports.com |publisher=CBS Sports |access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>  That same week, [[Pope Francis]] was gifted a Lamar Jackson Ravens jersey.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28227201/pope-francis-gifted-custom-ravens-jersey-signed-lamar-jackson?device=featurephone |title=Pope Francis gifted custom Ravens jersey signed by Lamar Jackson |last=Hensley |first=Jamison |date=December 4, 2019 |website=espn.com |publisher=ESPN |access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, [[Academy Award]] winning actor [[Al Pacino]], who starred in the football themed movie ''[[Any Given Sunday]]'', said:<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theringer.com/movies/2019/12/19/21027886/any-given-sunday-oral-history |title=Football Is a Dark Place\": The Oral History of \u2018Any Given Sunday\u2019 |last=Kring-Schreifels |first=Jake |date=December 19, 2019 |website=theringer.com |publisher=The Ringer |access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://uproxx.com/sports/al-pacino-lamar-jackson-ravens-inspiration/ |title=Al Pacino Looks At Lamar Jackson As An \u2018Inspiration\u2019 |last=Kalland |first=Robby |date=December 19, 2019 |website=uproxx.com |publisher=Uproxx |access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n{{quote| I watch this guy Lamar Jackson. There are occasionally these players that are inspiring because you can see the game that they play is a game, and you can actually sense the joy they have in what they do. That\u2019s inspiring. Watching Lamar Jackson is an inspiration to actors.}}\nIn February 2020, [[BET|BET Digital]]  highlighted Jackson as one of 40 of the most inspiring and innovative vanguards in African American culture and who are redefining what it means to be \"unapologetically young, gifted & Black\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://chicagodefender.com/bet-digital-celebrates-black-excellence-with-new-original-editorial-series/|title=BET DIGITAL CELEBRATES BLACK EXCELLENCE WITH NEW ORIGINAL EDITORIAL SERIES|date=2020-02-07|website=Chicago Defender|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Lamar jackson ravens camp 2018 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left]]\n{{Asof|2019}}, Jackson lives in [[Owings Mills, Maryland]], about 20 minutes from the Ravens training complex with his mother, brother, and sisters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/features/baltimore-insider/bs-fe-what-we-know-about-lamar-jackson-20191201-fe4x6qourfd53bn532vzws52ay-story.html |title=You\u2019ve heard about Lamar Jackson, the star Ravens QB. Here\u2019s what we know about Lamar Jackson, the person. |last=Miller |first=Hallie |date=December 1, 2019 |website=[[Baltimore Sun]] |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Jackson is a [[Christianity|Christian]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sportsspectrum.com/sport/football/2019/12/19/baltimore-ravens-qb-lamar-jackson-the-lord-keeps-him-humble/ |title=Baltimore Ravens QB Lamar Jackson on who keeps him humble: 'The Lord' |last=Ackerman |first=Jon |date=December 19, 2019 |website=Sports Spectrum |access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> Jackson's pre-game meal is shrimp alfredo pasta and his favorite [[superhero]] is [[Superman]].<ref>{{cite web |title=LAMAR JACKSON |url=http://www.ravenspr.com/player_bios/lamar_jackson.pdf |website=baltimoreravens.com |publisher=Baltimore Ravens |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of NCAA major college football yearly total offense leaders]]\n*[[List of NCAA Division I FBS career rushing touchdowns leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter|Lj_era8}}\n* [https://www.baltimoreravens.com/team/players-roster/lamar-jackson/ Baltimore Ravens bio]\n* [http://www.gocards.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=6038&path=football Louisville Cardinals bio]\n* {{Heisman|id=369|name=Lamar Jackson}}\n\n{{Baltimore Ravens roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Lamar Jackson\u2014awards and honors\n| list =\n{{Heisman Trophy}}\n{{Maxwell Award}}\n{{Walter Camp Award}}\n{{AP Players of the Year}}\n{{Sporting News College Football Player of the Year}}\n{{ACC Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{2016 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Louisville Cardinals quarterback navbox}}\n{{2018 NFL Draft}}\n{{RavensFirstPick}}\n{{Ravens2018DraftPicks}}\n{{Baltimore Ravens starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{AP NFL MVPs}}\n{{FedEx NFL Players}}\n{{NFL Quarterbacks with a Perfect Passer Rating}}\n{{NFL passing touchdown leaders}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Lamar}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century African-American people]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Ravens players]]\n[[Category:Heisman Trophy winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Louisville Cardinals football players]]\n[[Category:Maxwell Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Pompano Beach, Florida]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Boynton Beach, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{about|the quarterback|the former Nebraska cornerback|Lamar Jackson (cornerback)}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Lamar Jackson\n| image = Lamar Jackson.jpg   \n| image_size = 250px\n| alt = \n| caption = Jackson in 2019\n| current_team = Baltimore Ravens \n| number = 8\n| position = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|1|7|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pompano Beach, Florida]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 2\n| weight_lb = 212\n| high_school = [[Boynton Beach Community High School|Boynton Beach Community]]<br/>([[Boynton Beach, Florida]])\n| college = [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| draftyear = 2018\n| draftround = 1\n| draftpick = 32\n| pastteams = \n* [[Baltimore Ravens]] ({{NFL Year|2018}}\u2013present)\n| status = Active\n| highlights =\n* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2019 All-Pro Team|2019]])\n* [[Associated Press NFL Most Valuable Player Award|NFL Most Valuable Player]] ([[2019 NFL season|2019]])\n* [[List of National Football League annual passing touchdowns leaders|NFL passing touchdowns leader]] ([[2019 NFL season|2019]])\n* [[Bert Bell Award]] (2019)\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] (2016)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2016)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2016)\n* [[Associated Press College Football Player of the Year|Associated Press Player of the Year]] (2016)\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year|''Sporting News'' Player of the Year]] (2016)\n* Unanimous [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2016 College Football All-America Team|2016]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Atlantic Coast Conference football individual awards#Player of the Year|ACC Player of the Year]] (2016, 2017)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Atlantic Coast Conference football individual awards#Offensive Player of the Year|ACC Offensive Player of the Year]] (2016, 2017)\n* [[ACC Athlete of the Year]] (2018)\n;NFL records\n* Most rushing yards in a season by a quarterback (1,206) (2019)\n* Most rushing attempts by a quarterback in a season: 159 (2019)\n* Most perfect passer ratings in a season (tied with Ben Roethlisberger): 2 (2019)\n| statseason          = 2019\n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = [[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue1          = 42\u20139\n| statlabel2          = Passing yards\n| statvalue2          = 4,328\n| statlabel3          = Completion percentage\n| statvalue3          = 63.7\n| statlabel4          = Passer rating\n| statvalue4          = 104.7\n| statlabel5          = Rushing yards\n| statvalue5          = 1,901 \n| statlabel6          = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue6          = 12\n| nflnew = lamarjackson/2560757\n| pfr = JackLa00\n}}\n\n'''Lamar Demeatrice Jackson Jr.''' (born January 7, 1997) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[Baltimore Ravens]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]] where he won the [[Heisman Trophy]], [[Maxwell Award]], [[Walter Camp Award]], and was unanimously selected as an [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] as a sophomore in 2016.\n\nJackson was selected with the 32nd overall pick by the Ravens in the first round of the [[2018 NFL Draft]]. He began his rookie season as a backup, but became the team's starting quarterback following an injury to starter [[Joe Flacco]]. During the season, Jackson helped the team clinch the [[AFC North]] division title and became the youngest quarterback to start a playoff game. In 2019, his first full season as starter, Jackson set a record for the most rushing yards in a season by a quarterback<ref name=favorite/> and [[List of National Football League annual passing touchdowns leaders|led the league]] with 36 touchdown passes.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schiller |first1=Joe |title=Late for Work 12/30: Ravens Finish Regular Season in Style vs. Steelers |url=https://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/late-for-work-12-30-ravens-finish-regular-season-in-style-vs-steelers |website=baltimoreravens.com |publisher=Baltimore Ravens |accessdate=December 30, 2019}}</ref> Jackson was named the [[Associated Press NFL Most Valuable Player Award|NFL Most Valuable Player]] for 2019, becoming only the second-ever unanimous selection for the award.<ref name=\"ESPNMVP\">{{cite web |last1=Jamison |first1=Hensley |title=Ravens QB Lamar Jackson unanimous pick for NFL MVP after historic season |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28614953/ravens-qb-lamar-jackson-unanimous-pick-nfl-mvp-historic-season |website=ESPN |accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nJackson was born to Felicia Jones and Lamar Jackson, Sr., on January 7, 1997,<ref name=\"ESPN bio\" /> and grew up in the center of an economically distressed section of [[Pompano Beach, Florida]]. Lamar Sr. died in a car accident on the same day Lamar's grandmother died in 2005 when Jackson was eight and he and his siblings were thereafter raised by their mother.<ref name=\"mom\">{{cite web |last1=Rosenberg |first1=Todd |title=Lamar Jackson, His Mother, and the Plan They\u2019ve Always Had |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/04/03/lamar-jackson-mother-felicia-jones-draft-agent-manager-louisville |website=si.com |publisher=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=jacksonworked/> He attended public schools and played [[Pop Warner football]] in the same Florida league with Ravens wide receiver [[Marquise Brown]], though they were on different teams, with Jackson playing for the Pompano Beach Cowboys.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ftp.ravenspr.com/player_bios/marquise_brown.pdf |title=Marquise Brown |website=Baltimoreravens.com |publisher=Baltimore Ravens |access-date=September 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"jacksonworked\">{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Childs |title=How Lamar Jackson used more than talent to rise from the fields of South Florida: \u2018He continued to work\u2019 |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/bs-sp-ravens-lamar-jackson-origins-20191126-cnqpz2aalfauni6fofhlxvom2y-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com |publisher=Baltimore Sun |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Jackson's cousin, [[Oakland Raiders]] cornerback [[Trayvon Mullen]], and [[Atlanta Falcons]] wide receiver [[Calvin Ridley]] also competed against Jackson in that league.<ref>{{cite web |title=8 Lamar Jackson weekly bio update |url=http://ftp.ravenspr.com/bio_updates_player/jackson_lamar.pdf |website=baltimoreravens.com |publisher=Baltimore Ravens |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref> Growing up, his favorite player was [[Michael Vick]].<ref name=\"favorite\">{{cite web |last1=Mink |first1=Ryan |title=Michael Vick\u2019s Quarterback Rushing Record |url=https://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/lamar-jackson-breaks-michael-vick-s-quarterback-rushing-record |website=baltimoreravens.com |publisher=Baltimore Ravens |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref> At age 8, Jackson could throw a football 20 yards according to his first quarterback coach, Van \"Peanut\" Wilson and while he was in high school a homemade video shows him throwing a football 100 yards.<ref name=jacksonworked/><ref>{{cite web |title=Do You Believe the Legend of Lamar Jackson's 100-Yard Throw? |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b7EkDtkO5l4 |website=YouTube |publisher=Baltimore Ravens |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Louisville Quarterback Lamar Jackson Once Threw a Football 100 Yards, and Here's the Video to Prove it |url=https://www.stack.com/a/louisville-quarterback-lamar-jackson-once-threw-a-football-100-yards-and-heres-the-video-to-prove-it |website=stack.com |publisher=Stack Sports |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| width  = 300px\n| video1 =[https://www.maxpreps.com/video/watch/lamar-jackson-high-school-football-highlights?v=5ee46ba1-ce79-4182-847e-5289f01b3232 Lamar Jackson high school football highlights] MaxPreps video\n}}\nJackson first attended [[Santaluces Community High School]] where he played [[High school football|football]] sporadically and sat out his sophomore year. He then transferred to [[Boynton Beach High School]] in [[Boynton Beach, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/fl-sp-lamar-jackson-nfl-draft-20180424-story.html |title=Former Boynton Beach quarterback Lamar Jackson out to silence NFL doubters |last=Richardson |first=Shandel |date=April 24, 2018 |work=Sun-Sentinel.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAt Boynton Beach, Jackson played two seasons of [[Varsity team|varsity]] football.  Boynton Beach coach Rick Swain remembered Jackson as a hard worker who continually improved his passing accuracy and decision-making and who watched hours of film each week.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Steve |title=4-star QB Lamar Jackson picks U of L |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/recruiting/2014/08/30/four-star-florida-qb-lamar-jackson-picks-louisville/14877079/ |website=courier-journal.com |publisher=USA Today Network |accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref> In his two years (16 games) at Boynton Beach, Jackson threw for 2,263 yards and 31 touchdowns, ran for 1,624 yards and 22 touchdowns, and a high school career accumulated quarterback rating of 102.7.<ref name=\"boynton\">{{cite web|title=Lamar Jackson's Football Stats|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athlete/lamar-jackson/rcOGRBAIEeOZ5AAmVebBJg/gendersport/football-stats.htm|website=Max Preps|access-date=November 21, 2016}}</ref> Jackson's last high school game came against a nationally ranked [[Miami Central High School]] team during the first round of the 2014 Florida High School Football Playoff 6A tournament. Boynton Beach was soundly defeated 49\u20136, with Jackson throwing two interceptions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Furones |first1=David |title=Miami Central near perfect against Boynton Beach |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/high-school/prep-miami-dade/article3947969.html |website=miamiherald.com |publisher=Miami Herald |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref>  He also competed for his high school track team, posting a personal record of 11.45 seconds in the 100 meter dash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.athletic.net/TrackAndField/Athlete.aspx?AID=7077493|title=Lamar Jackson|website=Athletic.net|language=en|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref> Jackson was named the [[Lou Groza]] Palm Beach County High School Player of the Year in 2014,<ref name=\"Groza\">{{cite web |last1=Dusenbury |first1=Wells |title=Boynton Beach High alum Lamar Jackson makes NFL history with electric performance |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/highschool/football/palm-beach/fl-sp-hs-lamar-jackson-nfl-20191014-5chcmb7phzhgvfn2hwcagn34xm-story.html |website=sun-sentinel.com |publisher=South Florida Sun-Sentinel |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref> was rated by [[Rivals.com]] as a four-star recruit and had dozens of offers from big college football programs but he committed to the [[University of Louisville]] after head coach [[Bobby Petrino]] gave his word to Felicia Jones that her son would be playing quarterback and nothing else.<ref name=mom/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/7973 |title=Lamar Jackson, 2015 Dual-threat quarterback |website=Rivals.com |access-date=December 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/recruiting/2014/08/30/four-star-florida-qb-lamar-jackson-picks-louisville/14877079/ |title=Four-star Florida QB Lamar Jackson picks Louisville |last=Jones |first=Steve |date=August 30, 2014 |website=Courier-Journal |access-date=December 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/highschool/football/palm-beach/fl-palm-boynton-beach-signings-0205-20150204-story.html|title=Gator bait? QB Lamar Jackson fakes Florida, goes Louisville|first=Steve|last=Dorsey|work=Sun Sentinel|access-date=December 11, 2016|date=February 4, 2015}}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|! colspan=\"14\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|NCAA Division IA|border=no|color=white}}; text-align: center;\"|''' Florida High School 6A career statistics'''<ref name=boynton/>\n|-\n|! colspan=\"14\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|LSU Tigers|border=no|color=white}}; text-align: center;\"|'''Boynton Beach Tigers'''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"7\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yards !! TD !! Int !! Rate !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n! 2013\n| 9 || 9 || 70 || 163 || 42.9 || 1,264 || 19 || 6 || 93.7 || 102 || 960 || 9.4 || 10\n|-\n! 2014\n| 7 || 7 || 53 || 98 || 54.1 || 999 || 12 || 3 || 116.5 || 90 || 664 || 7.4 || 12\n|-\n! Career !! 16 !! 16 !! 123 !! 261 !! 47.1 !! 2,263 !! 31 !! 9 !! 102.7 !! 192 !! 1,624 !! 8.5 !! 22\n|}\n\n==College career==\n===Freshman year===\nAs a freshman at Louisville in 2015, Jackson played in 12 games and made eight starts. He completed 135-of-247 passes for 1,840 yards with 12 [[touchdown]]s and eight [[interception]]s and ran for 960 yards and 11 rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/ncfnation/post/_/id/124610/behind-lamar-jackson-expectations-rising-at-louisville |title=Behind Lamar Jackson, expectations rising at Louisville |last=Adelson |first=Andrea |date=January 14, 2016 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=December 11, 2016}}</ref> He was named the MVP of the [[2015 Music City Bowl]] after passing for 227 yards with two touchdowns and rushing for a [[Music City Bowl]]-record 226 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/lamar-jackson-introduces-himself-to-the-world-in-music-city-bowl-win/ |title=Lamar Jackson introduces himself to the world in Music City Bowl win |last=Fornelli |first=Tom |date=December 30, 2015 |website=CBS Sports |access-date=December 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-football/news/lamar-jackson-music-city-bowl-stats-louisville-texas-am/t8glmgqc6en0z3vdrgu6aixs |title=Music City Monster: Louisville's Lamar Jackson unstoppable against Texas A&M |last=Clements |first=Ron |date=December 31, 2015 |website=Sporting News |access-date=December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Sophomore year===\nDuring the first game of his sophomore year, against the [[Charlotte 49ers football|Charlotte 49ers]], Jackson set a school record for total touchdowns with eight, all of them in the first half.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://draftwire.usatoday.com/2016/09/02/watch-louisvilles-lamar-jackson-score-eight-first-half-touchdowns/ |title=Watch Louisville's Lamar Jackson score eight first-half touchdowns |last=Easterling |first=Luke |date=September 2, 2016 |work=USA Today |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> Against [[Syracuse Orange football|Syracuse]], Jackson completed 20 of 39 passes for 411 yards, one touchdown, and one interception, with 199 rushing yards and 4 rushing touchdowns, with all five touchdowns coming in the first half.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/ff645725213d49aabdb3bb98cf5571c8/Jackson-leads-No.-13-Louisville-past-Syracuse,-62-28 |title=Jackson leads No. 13 Louisville past Syracuse, 62\u201328 |last=Kekis |first=John |date=September 10, 2016 |work=AP NEWS |access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref> Against #2 [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]], Jackson completed 13 of 20 passes for 216 yards, threw one touchdown and one interception, and had 146 rushing yards and 4 rushing touchdowns. He scored 4 of the 5 total touchdowns in the first half. The game made Jackson the Heisman front runner,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/sports/wp/2016/12/10/lamar-jacksons-heisman-trophy-triumph-a-story-over-20-years-in-the-making/ |title=Lamar Jackson's Heisman Trophy triumph a story over 20 years in the making |last=Culpepper |first=Chuck  |date=December 10, 2016 |work=The Washington Post |access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> and gave the Cardinals a No. 3 ranking, their highest since 2006.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000703928/article/lamar-jackson-accounts-for-five-tds-in-6320-rout-of-fsu |title=Lamar Jackson accounts for five TDs in 63\u201320 rout of FSU |last=Goodbread |first=Chase |date=September 17, 2016 |work=NFL.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/louisville/polls.html |title=Louisville Cardinals AP Poll History |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref> Against [[Marshall Thundering Herd football|Marshall]], Jackson completed 24 of 44 passes for 417 yards and 5 touchdowns, and had 62 rushing yards and 2 rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000708511/article/louisvilles-lamar-jackson-scores-7-tds-in-rout-of-marshall |title=Louisville's Lamar Jackson scores 7 TDs in rout of Marshall |last=Parr |first=Dan |work=NFL.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Against No. 5 [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]], Louisville's offense totaled 586 yards, with Jackson accounting for 295 passing yards, 162 rushing yards, and three total touchdowns (1 passing, 2 rushing). The Cardinals eventually lost the game 42\u201336.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/clemson-shows-it-still-has-guts-in-surviving-epic-performance-from-lamar-jackson/ |title=Clemson shows it still has guts in surviving epic performance from Lamar Jackson |last=Patterson |first=Chip |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On December 8, Jackson was awarded the [[Walter Camp Award]] as the player of the year and the [[Maxwell Award]] as the best all-around player in college football.<ref>{{cite news|title=Louisville QB Lamar Jackson wins Camp, Maxwell awards|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/colleges/2016/12/08/louisville-lamar-jackson-wins-camp-maxwell-awards/4qZvPBj2K4yec8VCLXGAWI/story.html|access-date=December 10, 2016|work=The Boston Globe|date=December 9, 2016}}</ref>\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| width  = 300px\n| video1 =[http://www.espn.com/video/clip/clip?id=18251828 Jackson's Heisman acceptance speech], ESPN video \n}}\n\nOn December 10, 2016, Jackson was selected as the 2016 Heisman Trophy winner over fellow finalists [[Deshaun Watson]], [[Dede Westbrook]], [[Jabrill Peppers]], and [[Baker Mayfield]]. He became Louisville's first Heisman Trophy winner in school history, and the youngest-ever recipient of the award at the age of 19 years and 337 days.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/12/10/sport/heisman-trophy/index.html |title=Louisville's Lamar Jackson wins Heisman |last=Martin |first=Jill |last2=Almasy |first2=Steve |website=CNN.com |access-date=December 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lamar Jackson 2016 |url=https://www.heisman.com/heisman-winners/lamar-jackson/ |website=heisman.com |publisher=Heisman Trust |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Willis |first1=Zack |title=The 5 Youngest Heisman Trophy Winners Reveal Growing Trend |url=https://www.sportscasting.com/the-5-youngest-heisman-trophy-winners-reveal-growing-trend/ |website=sportscasting.com |publisher=EndGame360 |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAside from nationally recognized awards, Jackson also won prestigious awards within the University of Louisville. In 2017, Jackson won a Louie for being named the Adidas High Performance Male Athlete of the Year for his outstanding sophomore campaign. He also won a Louie for Play of the Year after the leap he made in the 2016 [[Syracuse University|Syracuse]] game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/louisville/2017/04/18/lamar-jackson-big-winner-louie-awards/100594412/ |title=Lamar Jackson a big winner at U of L 'Louie' awards |last=Jones |first=Steve |work=The Courier-Journal |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Junior year===\nWhen Jackson entered the 2017 season, his fan base and media had high expectations of his performance.  ''[[College GameDay (football)|College GameDay]]'' announced their return to the University of Louisville to host the opening matchup on September 16 between the returning National Champions, Clemson Tigers, and the Cardinals. Despite the 47\u201321 blowout the Tigers achieved,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/recap?gameId=400937461 |title=No. 3 Clemson blows out Jackson and No. 14 Louisville, 47\u201321 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 29, 2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Jackson did not let the numbers affect his playing ability.  His remarkable statistics for the season resulted in his being a Heisman finalist for the 2017 season. He finished in third place in the Heisman voting, losing out to [[Baker Mayfield]] and [[Bryce Love]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/heisman-2017.html |title=2017 Heisman Trophy Voting |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref> Jackson played in 13 games, finishing with 3,660 passing yards, 27 touchdowns, and 10 interceptions.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/patriots/2018/04/23/patriots-are-reportedly-intrigued-and-impressed-after-hosting-lamar-jackson/ze6pXDIS5Riy7fxfYjEl9M/story.html |title=Patriots are reportedly \u2018intrigued and impressed\u2019 after hosting Lamar Jackson |last=Yang |first=Nicole |date=April 23, 2018 |work=BostonGlobe.com |access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2017\u201318 school year, Jackson was named the men's [[ACC Athlete of the Year]] for all conference sports, sharing honors with women's winner [[Arike Ogunbowale]] of [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish women's basketball|Notre Dame basketball]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://theacc.com/news/2018/7/5/general-louisvilles-jackson-notre-dames-ogunbowale-voted-acc-athletes-of-the-year.aspx |title=Louisville's Jackson, Notre Dame's Ogunbowale Voted ACC Athletes of the Year |publisher=[[Atlantic Coast Conference]] |date=July 5, 2018 |access-date=July 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Collegiate statistics===\nJackson's career college statistics were as follows:<ref name=\"ESPN bio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/player/stats/_/id/3916387/lamar-jackson |title=Lamar Jackson |publisher=ESPN.com |access-date=April 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|! colspan=\"14\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|NCAA Division I|border=no|color=white}}; text-align: center;\"|'''NCAA collegiate career statistics'''\n|-\n|! colspan=\"14\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Louisville Cardinals|border=no|color=white}}; text-align: center;\"|'''Louisville Cardinals'''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Season\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"7\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yards !! TD !! Int !! Rate !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n! [[2015 Louisville Cardinals football team|2015]]\n| 12 || 8 || 135 || 247 || 54.7 || 1,840 || 12 || 8 || 126.8 || 163 || 960 || 5.9 || 11\n|-\n! [[2016 Louisville Cardinals football team|2016]]\n| 13 || 13 || 230 || 409 || 56.2 || 3,543 || 30 || 9 || 148.8 || 260 || 1,571 || 6.0 || 21\n|-\n! [[2017 Louisville Cardinals football team|2017]]\n| 13 || 13 || 254 || 430 || 59.1 || 3,660 || 27 || 10 || 146.6 || 232 || 1,601 || 6.9 || 18\n|-\n! Career !! 38 !! 34 !! 619 !! 1,086 !! 57.0 !! 9,043 !! 69 !! 27 !! 142.9 !! 655 !! 4,132 !! 6.3 !! 50\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nOn January 5, 2018, Jackson announced that he would enter the [[2018 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Louisville QB Lamar Jackson intends to enter 2018 NFL Draft|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000902980/article/louisville-qb-lamar-jackson-intends-to-enter-2018-nfl-draft|publisher=NFL|accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref> Some draft pundits doubted Jackson's quarterback abilities and suggested that he switch positions due to his athleticism, but he remained adamant about his intention to play quarterback professionally. He declined to run drills such as the [[40-yard dash]] during the [[NFL Scouting Combine]], in order to focus on displaying his passing skills.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/columnist/bell/2018/03/02/insulting-louisville-quarterback-lamar-jackson-switch-wide-receiver/391256002/ | title=It\u2019s insulting to suggest Louisville quarterback Lamar Jackson should switch to wide receiver | publisher=USA Today Sports | date=March 2, 2018 | access-date=December 27, 2018 | author=Bell, Jarrett}}</ref> \n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| width  = 300px\n| video1 =[https://www.newyorkjets.com/video/lamar-jackson-combine-press-conference-20410901 Lamar Jackson 2018 NFL Combine press conference]\n| video2 =[https://www.baltimoreravens.com/video/watch-ravens-select-louisville-quarterback-lamar-jackson-20591004 Ravens draft Lamar Jackson], Baltimore Ravens video\n}}\n{{NFL predraft\n| height ft    = 6\n| height in    = 2\u00bc\n| weight       = 216\n| dash         = \n| ten split    = \n| twenty split = \n| shuttle      = \n| cone drill   = \n| vertical     = \n| broad ft     = \n| broad in     = \n| bench        = \n| wonderlic    = 13\n| arm span     = 33\u215b\n| hand span    = 9\u00bd\n| note         = All values from [[2018 NFL Draft|NFL Draft]]<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.nfl.com/prospects/lamar-jackson?id=32462018-0002-5600-53b1-0f1a50e94b24 | title = NFL Draft Prospect Profile \u2013 Lamar Jackson | work = nfl.com | date = March 1, 2018 | access-date = March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=1002867&draftyear=2018&genpos=qb | title = Louisville QB Lamar Jackson : 2018 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile | work = NFLDraftScout.com | access-date = May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\nJackson was drafted by the [[Baltimore Ravens]] in the first round with the 32nd overall pick in the draft; they traded up for the selection with the [[Philadelphia Eagles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ravens trade up to take Lamar Jackson at No. 32|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000929151/article/ravens-trade-up-to-take-lamar-jackson-at-no-32|author=Wesseling, Chris|website=NFL.com|date=April 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/ravens/vegas-odds-against-lamar-jackson-starting-ravens-2018|title=Vegas odds against Lamar Jackson starting for Ravens in 2018|date=May 14, 2018|work=NBC Sports Washington|access-date=May 30, 2018}}</ref> He was the fifth quarterback selected that year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/draft.htm |title=2018 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> On June 5, 2018, Jackson signed his rookie contract, reportedly worth $9.47 million with a $4.97 million signing bonus.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patra |first1=Kevin |title=Lamar Jackson signs rookie contract with Ravens |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000935824/article/lamar-jackson-signs-rookie-contract-with-ravens |website=nfl.com |publisher=National Football League |accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season: Rookie year===\nJackson made his NFL debut relieving starting quarterback [[Joe Flacco]] in the second half of a 47\u20133 victory against the [[2018 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], finishing with 24 passing yards and 39 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/louisville/2018/09/09/lamar-jackson-ravens-nfl-debut-stats/1249989002/ |title=Lamar Jackson plays plenty in NFL debut as Baltimore Ravens win big |last=Lourim |first=Jake |date=September 9, 2018 |work=The Courier-Journal |access-date=October 1, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> During Week 7, Jackson scored his first NFL touchdown on a 1-yard run as the Ravens narrowly lost to the [[2018 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]] by a score of 24\u201323.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/10/21/baltimore-ravens-lamar-jackson-scores-first-career-td-saints |title=Ravens' Lamar Jackson Scores First Career TD vs. Saints |last=Jones |first=Kaelen |date=October 21, 2018 |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=October 25, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Jackson threw his first NFL touchdown pass, a 26-yard completion to fellow rookie tight end [[Hayden Hurst]], the next week in relief of Flacco in the fourth quarter of a 36\u201321 loss to the [[2018 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://ravenswire.usatoday.com/2018/10/28/watch-qb-lamar-jackson-throws-1st-nfl-touchdown-pass/|title=Watch: QB Lamar Jackson throws 1st NFL touchdown pass |first=Kevin|last=Oestreicher|work=Ravens Wire|publisher=USAToday.com |access-date=October 28, 2018|date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lamar Jackson vs. Bengals 2018.jpg|thumb|Jackson versus [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]]]]\nOn November 18, 2018, Jackson made his first NFL  start against the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] in place of the injured [[Joe Flacco]], who injured his hip two weeks prior against the [[2018 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]]. Jackson went 13 for 19 for 150 yards and an interception and rushed for 117 yards, which was a Ravens franchise record for rushing yards by a quarterback in a single game in a 24\u201321 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/washington/ravens/what-rush-lamar-jackson-ran-117-yards-win |title=Lamar Jackson has 117 rushing yards in win |last=Hudson |first=Jamar |date=November 18, 2018 |work=NBC Sports Washington |access-date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> The following week against the [[2018 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], Jackson threw for 178 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions. He also rushed for 71 yards and a rushing touchdown. The Ravens won by a score of 34\u201317.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2018/11/25/baltimore-ravens-oakland-raiders-week-12/ |title=Lamar Jackson, Gus Edwards and Baltimore Ravens run over Oakland Raiders |last=Ginsburg |first=David |date=November 25, 2018 |work=The Denver Post |access-date=November 30, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> During Week 13 against the [[2018 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Jackson passed for 125 yards and rushed for 75 yards and a touchdown in a 26\u201316 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2808877-lamar-jackson-remains-undefeated-as-starter-as-ravens-beat-falcons-26-16 |title=Lamar Jackson Remains Undefeated as Starter as Ravens Beat Falcons 26\u201316 |last=Conway |first=Tyler |date=December 2, 2018 |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref> In a Week 14 27\u201324 overtime loss to the [[2018 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], Jackson threw two touchdowns for the first time in his career.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/bs-sp-ravens-chiefs-20181209-story.html |title=Instant analysis: Ravens fall apart late, fade in overtime of wild 27\u201324 loss to Chiefs |last=Shaffer |first=Jonas |date=December 9, 2018 |website=baltimoresun.com |language=en-US |access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nJackson helped the Ravens defeat the [[2018 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]] in Week 16, completing 12 of 22 passes for 204 yards and a touchdown in a 22\u201310 upset victory.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/12/23/lamar-jackson-baltimore-ravens-chargers-playoff-picture | title=Lamar Jackson leads Ravens to 22\u201310 victory over Chargers | publisher=Sports Illustrated | work=The Associated Press | date=December 23, 2018 | accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> The following week against fellow rookie quarterback [[Baker Mayfield]] and the [[2018 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Jackson passed for 179 yards and rushed for two touchdowns on 95 rushing yards, despite fumbling a third potential touchdown at the goal line, as the Ravens beat the Browns 26\u201324 to clinch the [[AFC North]] title.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/browns-vs-ravens-final-score-takeaways-baltimore-holds-off-baker-mayfields-final-charge-to-win-afc-north/ |title=Browns vs. Ravens final score, takeaways: Baltimore holds off Baker Mayfield's final charge to win AFC North |last=Wagner-McGough, Sean |date=December 30, 2018 |publisher=CBS Sports |access-date=December 31, 2018}}</ref> In the seven regular season games in which Jackson had started, the Ravens went 6\u20131 to close out the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25650325/rookie-qb-lamar-jackson-leads-baltimore-ravens-afc-north-title |title=Lamar Jackson leads Ravens to first postseason berth since 2014 |last=Hensley |first=Jamison |date=December 31, 2018 |publisher=ESPN.com |access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> Overall, he finished with 1,201 passing yards, six passing touchdowns, and three interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/passing.htm |title=2018 NFL Passing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref> In addition, he led all quarterbacks with 695 rushing yards and added five rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/rushing.htm |title=2018 NFL Rushing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Postseason====\nJackson became the youngest quarterback to ever start a playoff game when the Ravens faced off at home against the Chargers in a rematch during the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: Los Angeles Chargers 23, Baltimore Ravens 17|Wild Card Round]] of the playoffs. Despite being held to just 25 passing yards at one point in the fourth quarter by a stout Chargers defense, Jackson then passed for two touchdowns in four minutes to bring the Ravens back from a 20-point deficit to within a touchdown. After forcing the Chargers to punt with less than a minute left, the Ravens had one last chance to win the game down six points, but Jackson was strip-sacked by Chargers linebacker [[Uchenna Nwosu]]. With the Chargers recovering the ball, the Ravens lost 23\u201317 and were knocked out of the playoffs. He finished the game completing 14 of 29 passes for 194 yards, the two aforementioned touchdowns, and an interception while rushing for 54 yards, losing one fumble.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/bs-sp-ravens-chargers-lamar-jackson-20190106-story.html |title=At the end of a breakthrough rookie season, quarterback Lamar Jackson leaves Ravens needing more |last=Shaffer |first=Jonas |date=January 6, 2019 |work=The Baltimore Sun |access-date=September 19, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOnce the 2018 season was over, the Ravens's coaching staff decided to abandon the offensive strategy that had been designed for [[Joe Flacco]] and create a new offensive philosophy centered around the specific skills of Jackson. That philosophy included changing every play in the playbook, the terminology used and drafting players or acquiring free agents that would complement Jackson's skills.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kilgore |first1=Adam |title=The Ravens are all-in on Lamar Jackson, and their remade offense proves it |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/06/25/ravens-are-all-in-lamar-jackson-their-remade-offense-proves-it/ |website=washingtonpost.com |publisher=Washington Post |accessdate=November 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019 season: Unanimous NFL MVP===\nIn the season-opener against the [[2019 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], Jackson went 17 of 20 for career-high 324 yards and five touchdowns, making him the youngest quarterback to achieve a [[perfect passer rating]] in the 59\u201310 road victory. He was named AFC Offensive Player of the Week due to his performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2019090803/2019/REG1/ravens@dolphins|title=Watch Baltimore Ravens vs. Miami Dolphins [09/08/2019] including a live Drive Chart and real-time highlights|website=NFL.com|language=en-US|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001053523/article/lamar-jackson-dak-prescott-among-players-of-the-week |title=Lamar Jackson, Dak Prescott among Players of the Week |date=September 11, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=September 19, 2019}}</ref> During Week 2 against the [[2019 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]], Jackson rushed for 120 yards and threw for 272 yards and two touchdowns, as the Ravens won by a score of 23\u201317. His two touchdown passes set the Ravens' franchise record for the most touchdown passes in the team's first two games of a season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27622058/ravens-jackson-sets-team-record-7th-td |title=Ravens' Jackson sets team record with 7th TD |last=Hensley |first=Jamison |date=September 15, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN |access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cardinals v Ravens |url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2019091500/2019/REG2/cardinals@ravens |website=nfl.com |publisher=National Football League |access-date=September 15, 2019}}</ref> Jackson became the first player in NFL history to pass for more than 250 yards and rush for 120 yards in one game.<ref name=\"Platko\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.baltimorebeatdown.com/2019/9/16/20867757/ravens-vs-cardinals-by-the-numbers-baltimore-arizona-mark-andrews |title=Ravens vs. Cardinals: By the numbers |last=Platko |first=Frank J. |date=September 16, 2019 |website=Baltimore Beatdown |publisher=SB Nation |access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week 6 against the [[2019 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], Jackson finished with 236 passing yards, 152 rushing yards, and a rushing touchdown as the Ravens won 23\u201317. He also became the first player in NFL history to pass for more than 200 yards and rush for 150 yards in a regular-season game,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001065681/article/lamar-jackson-sets-records-in-dualthreat-performance |title=Lamar Jackson sets records in dual-threat performance |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=October 14, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> and had more rushing yards than any player at any position in Week 6.<ref>{{cite web |title=2019 Week 6 Leaders |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2019/week_6.htm}}</ref> During Week 7 against the [[2019 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], Jackson finished with 143 passing yards and 116 rushing yards with a rushing touchdown as the Ravens won 30\u201316.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127985 |title=Jackson's legs, Ravens defense roll past Seahawks 30\u201316 |date=October 20, 2019 |website=www.espn.com|agency=Associated Press |access-date=October 20, 2019}}</ref> After a Week 8 bye, the Ravens faced the unbeaten [[2019 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]. In that game, Jackson threw for 163 yards and a touchdown and rushed for 61 yards and two touchdowns in the 37\u201320 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127899 |title=Unbeaten no more, Patriots fall to Jackson and Ravens 37\u201320 |date=November 3, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 3, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> For his performance, Jackson earned his second AFC Offensive Player of the Week award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001073900/article/lamar-jackson-russell-wilson-among-players-of-the-week |title=Lamar Jackson, Russell Wilson among Players of the Week |date=November 6, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the next game, the Ravens routed the Bengals 49\u201313 with Jackson throwing for 223 yards and three touchdowns and rushing for 65 yards and a touchdown, finishing with a perfect passer rating. He became only the second player in NFL history to produce two perfect passer ratings in the same season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28051772/lamar-jackson-joins-elite-club-perfect-passer-rating |title=Lamar Jackson joins elite club with perfect passer rating |last=Hensley |first=Jamison |publisher=ESPN.com |access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref>  Jackson joined [[Aaron Rodgers]] (2019) and [[Joe Montana]] (1989) as the only players in the Super Bowl era with 15-plus completions, 3-plus passing touchdowns, 1-plus rushing touchdowns, and a perfect passer rating in a single game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001075838/article/lamar-jackson-adds-signature-moment-to-mvp-resume |title=Lamar Jackson adds signature moment to MVP resume |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=November 11, 2019 |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> Jackson also earned his third total, and second consecutive, AFC Offensive Player of the Week award, matching his predecessor [[Joe Flacco]]'s career total.<ref>{{cite web |last=Alper |first=Josh |title=Lamar Jackson takes second straight AFC offensive player of the week |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2019/11/13/lamar-jackson-takes-another-afc-offensive-player-of-the-week/ |date=November 13, 2019 |website=ProFootballTalk |access-date=November 13, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Jackson v Texans 2019.jpg|thumb|280px|Jackson versus [[2019 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] ]]\nDuring Week 11 against the [[2019 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Jackson became the first quarterback in franchise history to throw four or more touchdowns in a game multiple times during the regular season after he threw for 222 yards and four touchdowns in a 41\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/chalk/story/_/id/28108572/ravens-qb-lamar-jackson-favored-las-vegas-win-mvp |title=Ravens QB Lamar Jackson favored by Las Vegas to win MVP |last=Purdum |first=David |date=November 18, 2019 |publisher=ESPN.com |access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Jackson also rushed for 86 yards during the victory over the Texans making him the only quarterback in NFL history to rush for more than 60 yards in seven consecutive games.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reed |first1=Jesse |title=LAMAR JACKSON MAKES NFL HISTORY SURPASSING MICHAEL VICK IN RECORD BOOKS |url=https://sportsnaut.com/2019/11/lamar-jackson-makes-nfl-history-surpassing-michael-vick-in-record-books/ |website=sportsnaut.com |publisher=SPORTSNAUT, LLC |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], Jackson threw for 169 yards and five touchdowns in the 45\u20136 road victory, making him the first player with that many touchdowns in a ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' debut and the youngest player with multiple five touchdown passing games in NFL history.<ref name=Hensley/> He earned his fourth [[American Football Conference|AFC]] Offensive Player of the Week award due to his performance.<ref name=\"player\">{{cite web |last1=Gordon |first1=Grant |title=Lamar Jackson, Chris Godwin among players of the week |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001081160/article/lamar-jackson-chris-godwin-among-players-of-the-week |website=nfl.com |publisher=The National Football League |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref> He was named the [[American Football Conference|AFC]]'s Player of the Month for November.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001084114/article/lamar-jackson-among-players-of-the-month-for-nov |title=Lamar Jackson among Players of the Month for Nov. |last=Gordon |first=Grant |date=December 5, 2019 |website=NFL.com |publisher=The National Football League |access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2019 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]], Jackson finished with 105 passing yards, 101 rushing yards, and two total touchdowns as the Ravens won 20\u201317,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/01/sports/football/ravens-49ers-score-lamar-jackson.html |title=Ravens Outlast 49ers With a Strong Finishing Kick |last=Shpigel |first=Ben |date=December 1, 2019 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> and Jackson became the first quarterback in NFL history with four 100-yard rushing games in a season.<ref>{{cite web |title=100-yard QB rushers, by season |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/ksRrn |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref> In Week 14, in the 24\u201317 victory over the [[2019 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Jackson became the first quarterback since Michael Vick to rush for 1,000 yards in a single season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pennlive.com/baltimore-ravens/2019/12/baltimore-ravens-lamar-jackson-hits-1000-rushing-yards-but-bills-stay-close-1st-half-highlights.html |title=Baltimore Ravens\u2019 Lamar Jackson hits 1,000 rushing yards, but Bills stay close |date=December 8, 2019 |website=PennLive |language=en |access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a nationally televised ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' game against the [[2019 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] in Week 15, Jackson had 212 passing yards for five touchdowns, and eight rushes for 86 yards during the 42\u201321 win, breaking Vick's single-season rushing record for a quarterback.<ref name=favorite/> His five passing touchdowns in the game made him the sixth player since the merger to have three games with at least five passing touchdowns in a season, and tied the Ravens franchise season record with 33.<ref>{{cite web |title=New York Jets at Baltimore Ravens - December 12th, 2019 |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201912120rav.htm |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/jets-at-ravens-final-score-lamar-jackson-has-another-five-touchdown-game-as-baltimore-rolls/live/ |title=Lamar Jackson has another five touchdown game as Baltimore rolls |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>  After his performance against the Jets, Jackson was named AFC Player of the Week for week 15.<ref name=week15/> In Week 16 against the [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Jackson was held to 38 passing yards and a lost fumble in the first 28 minutes, before exploding for 142 yards and two touchdowns in the last two minutes before halftime. He added a third touchdown pass in the second half of the 31\u201315 win, setting the Ravens single season record for touchdown passes at 36,<ref name=\"passingrecord\">{{cite web |last1=Hensley |first1=Jamison |title=Lamar Jackson sets TD record as Ravens get No. 1 seed |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28353194/lamar-jackson-sets-td-record-ravens-get-no-1-seed |website=eson.com |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=December 22, 2019}}</ref> finishing with 238 passing yards and 103 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/playbyplay?gameId=401127904|title=Ravens vs. Browns - Play-By-Play - December 22, 2019 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> On the day after the Ravens' victory over the Browns, and due to the Ravens' having clinched home-field advantage, head coach [[John Harbaugh]] announced that Jackson, guard [[Marshal Yanda]], safety [[Earl Thomas]] and defensive tackle [[Brandon Williams (defensive tackle)|Brandon Williams]] would be inactive for the Week 17 game against the [[2019 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shaffer |first1=Jonas |title=Lamar Jackson, three other Ravens starters will sit out regular-season finale vs. Steelers |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/ravens/bs-sp-ravens-lamar-jackson-steelers-20191223-nwow2wzic5eqrkkznolebthb2m-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com |publisher=Baltimore Sun |accessdate=December 24, 2019}}</ref>  Even without playing in the Ravens final game, Jackson  led all quarterbacks with 36 touchdown passes and a [[Total quarterback rating|QBR]] of 81.10; he also led all rushers with a 6.9 yards per carry average.<ref name=\"2019leaders\">{{cite web |title=2019 NFL Leaders and Leaderboards |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2019/leaders.htm |website=pro-football-reference.com |publisher=Pro Football Reference |accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref> During the 2019 season he was also first with 43 total touchdowns and a 9.0 passing touchdown percentage.<ref name=super8/>\n\n====Postseason====\nIn the Divisional round versus the [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], Jackson and the Ravens were not able to recreate the same success that they had in the regular season, losing 28\u201312.<ref>{{cite web |title=Baltimore Ravens vs. Tennessee Titans 2019 Postseason|url=https://www.espn.com/blog/tennessee-titans/post/_/id/29187/titans-all-too-familiar-formula-puts-tennessee-in-the-afc-championship%3fplatform=amp |website=espn.com |publisher= ESPN |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>  Jackson finished the game completing 31 of 59 passes for 365 yards, 1 touchdown and 2 interceptions.  He also rushed 20 times for 143 yards becoming the first player to throw for 300+ yards and rush for 100+ yards in a playoff game.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131041 |title=Titans stun Ravens, head to AFC title game with 28-12 win |date=January 11, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mink|first=Ryan|title=Lamar Jackson Shakes Off Haters After Another Playoff Loss|url=https://www.baltimoreravens.com/news/lamar-jackson-shakes-off-haters-after-another-playoff-loss|publisher=Baltimore Ravens|website=BaltimoreRavens.com|date=January 12, 2020|accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref> In total, Jackson personally accounted for over 500 yards of offense.\n\nJackson was the starting quarterback at the [[2020 Pro Bowl]] in [[Orlando, Florida]]. He threw  for 185 yards and two touchdowns with one interception and was named the offensive Most Valuable Player. He became the youngest quarterback in NFL history to start a Pro Bowl game.<ref name=\"2020pro\">{{cite web |last1=DiRocco |first1=Michael |title=Ravens' Lamar Jackson named Offensive MVP at Pro Bowl |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/28571114/ravens-lamar-jackson-named-offensive-mvp-pro-bowl |website=espn.com |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nJackson was voted the [[Associated Press NFL Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] of the 2019 season.<ref name=\"ESPNMVP\"/>  He became the second player in history after [[Tom Brady]] to be voted unanimously<ref>{{cite web |title=Baltimore Ravens QB Lamar Jackson named 2019 NFL MVP|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/football/nfl/baltimore-ravens-qb-lamar-jackson-named-2019-nfl-mvp/ |website=sportsnet.ca |publisher=Sportsnet |accessdate= 1 February 2020}}</ref> and the second-youngest player to win, behind only [[Jim Brown]].<ref name=\"ESPNMVP\"/> Jackson, along with [[Patrick Mahomes]], [[Cam Newton]] and [[Steve McNair]], is one of the four [[List of starting black NFL quarterbacks|African-American quarterbacks]] to win the AP MVP award.<ref>{{cite web |title=MVP Patrick Mahomes is now part of the legendary black quarterback fraternity |url=https://theundefeated.com/features/mvp-patrick-mahomes-is-now-part-of-the-legendary-black-quarterback-fraternity/ |website=TheUndefeated.com}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n[[File:Jackson passing sidearm.jpg|thumb|Lamar Jackson's \"[[sidearm (baseball)|sidearm]]\" style]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"| \n| Led the league\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e0cef2; width:3em;\"|\n| NFL record for quarterback\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FFFF00; width:3em;\"|\n| AP [[NFL MVP]]\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{|style=\"cellpadding=1; text-align:center;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold;background:#000000;color:White;\"\n| colspan=\"4\" | Teams || colspan=\"8\" | Passing || colspan=\"4\" | Rushing\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold;background:#24135F;color:#9A7611;\"\n| Season || Team || GP || GS || Comp || Att || Pct || Yds || Avg || TD || Int || Rate || Att || Yds || Avg || TD\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Baltimore Ravens season|BAL]] \n| '''16''' || 7 || 99 || 170 || 58.2 || 1,201 || 7.1 || 6 || 3 || 84.5 || 147 || 695 || 4.7 || 5\n|-\n! style=\"background:#FFFF00;\"|[[2019 NFL season|2019]] || [[2019 Baltimore Ravens season|BAL]]\n| 15 || '''15''' || '''265''' || '''401''' || '''66.1''' || '''3,127''' || '''7.8''' || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|'''36''' || '''6''' || '''113.3''' || '''176''' || style=\"background:#e0cef2; width:3em;\"|'''1,206''' || style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|'''6.9''' || '''7'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 31 || 22 || 364 || 571 || 63.7 || 4,328 || 7.6 || 42 || 9 || 104.7 || 323 || 1,901 || 5.9 || 12\n|}\n\n====Postseason====\n{|style=\"cellpadding=1; text-align:center;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold;background:#000000;color:White;\"\n| colspan=\"4\" | Teams || colspan=\"8\" | Passing || colspan=\"4\" | Rushing\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold;background:#24135F;color:#9A7611;\"\n| Season || Team || GP || GS || Comp || Att || Pct || Yds || Avg || TD || Int || 