chive.org/web/20150709151425/http://rugby7.com/st.asp?T=LAX-2004 |df=dmy}}\n</ref>\n\n===Results by team===\nUpdated to include the 2020 tournamenent:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:95%;\"\n|-\n!width=15%|Team\n!width=20%|Champions\n!width=24%|Runners-up\n!width=22%|Semifinalists\n|-\n|{{ru7|RSA}}\n|2011, 2013, 2014, 2017, 2020\n|2008\n|2009, 2012, 2015, 2016, 2018\n|-\n|{{ru7|FIJ}}\n|2007, 2015, 2016\n|2006, 2011, 2017, 2020\n|2012, 2013, 2018\n|-\n\n|{{ru7|NZL}}\n|2005, 2008\n|2004, 2010, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015\n|2007, 2011, 2017, 2019, 2020\n|-\n|{{ru7|ARG}}\n|2004, 2009\n|2005, 2018\n|2019\n|-\n|{{ru7|SAM}}\n|2010, 2012\n|2007, 2019\n|2008, 2013, 2014\n|-\n|{{ru7|USA}}\n|2018, 2019\n|\n|2009, 2015, 2016, 2017\n|-\n|{{ru7|ENG}}\n|2006\n|2009\n|2005, 2011\n|-\n|{{ru7|AUS}}\n| \n|2016\n|2010, 2020\n|-\n|{{ru7|KEN}}\n| \n| \n|2008, 2010\n|-\n|{{ru7|CAN}}\n| \n| \n|2014\n|-\n|{{ru7|FRA}}\n| \n| \n|2007\n|-\n|}\n\n===Leading scorers===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%; width: 90%; text-align: center;\"\n|+'''Leading Tournament Scorers'''\n!width=\"50\"|Season\n! style=\"width:200px;\"|Tries\n! style=\"width:190px;\"|Points\n|-\n|[[2004 USA Sevens|2004]]\n|??\n|??\n|-\n|[[2005 USA Sevens|2005]]\n|8-[[Tafai Ioasa]] (New Zealand)\n|61-[[Orene Ai'i]] (New Zealand)\n|-\n|[[2006 USA Sevens|2006]]\n|9-[[David Strettle]] (England)\n|59-[[Ben Gollings]] (England)\n|-\n|[[2007 USA Sevens|2007]]\n|6-(several)\n|56-[[William Ryder (rugby)|William Ryder]] (Fiji)\n|-\n|[[2008 USA Sevens|2008]]\n|8-[[Chris Wyles]] (USA) & [[Victor Vito (rugby player)|Victor Vito]] (NZ)\n|51-[[Ben Gollings]] (England)\n|-\n|[[2009 USA Sevens|2009]]\n|8-[[Viliame Waqasduadua]] (New Zealand)\n|48-[[Peni Rokodiva]] (Fiji)\n|-\n|[[2010 USA Sevens|2010]]\n|11-[[Mikaele Pesamino]] (Samoa)\n|55-[[Mikaele Pesamino]] (Samoa)\n|-\n|[[2011 USA Sevens|2011]]\n|10-[[Collins Injera]] (Kenya)\n|54-[[Cecil Afrika]] (South Africa)\n|-\n|[[2012 USA Sevens|2012]]\n|7-[[Cecil Afrika]] (South Africa)\n|44-[[Tomasi Cama]] (New Zealand)\n|-\n|[[2013 USA Sevens|2013]]\n|8-[[Lewis Holland]] (Australia)\n|52-[[Lewis Holland]] (Australia)\n|-\n|[[2014 USA Sevens|2014]]\n|6-[[Seabelo Senatla]] (South Africa)\n|48-[[Cameron Clark (rugby union)|Cameron Clark]] (Australia)\n|-\n|[[2015 USA Sevens|2015]]\n| 7- [[Savenaca Rawaca]] (Fiji)\n| \n|-\n|[[2016 USA Sevens|2016]]\n| 11- [[Seabelo Senatla]] (South Africa)\n| \n|-\n|[[2017 USA Sevens|2017]]\n| 7 \u2013 [[Lachie Anderson]] (Australia)\n| 39 \u2013 [[Ethan Davies]] (Wales)\n|-\n| [[2018 USA Sevens|2018]]\n| 8 \u2013 [[Perry Baker]] (United States)\n| 45 \u2013 [[Nathan Hirayama]] (Canada)\n|-\n| [[2019 USA Sevens|2019]]\n| 8 \u2013 [[Carlin Isles]] (United States)\n| 53 \u2013 [[Nathan Hirayama]] (Canada)\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[World Rugby Sevens Series]]\n* [[Sports in Las Vegas]]\n* [[USA Women's Sevens]]\n* [[Rugby union in the United States]]\n* [[United States national rugby sevens team]]\n* [[Canada Sevens]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.usasevens.com/  Official USA Sevens Homepage]\n*[http://www.irbsevens.com/NR/rdonlyres/6B76642D-2E58-4602-AF6E-21FDFC04EC99/0/USA7salltime.pdf All-Time Event Records]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100209183245/http://www.irb.com/irbsevens/edition=4/index.html Official IRB homepage for USA Sevens]\n*[http://www.rugby7.com/index.asp Index of World Sevens series]\n\n{{USA Sevens}}\n{{World sevens series}}\n{{Rugby union in the USA}}\n{{Las Vegas Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Usa Sevens}}\n[[Category:USA Sevens| ]]\n[[Category:World Rugby Sevens Series tournaments]]\n[[Category:International rugby union competitions hosted by the United States]]\n[[Category:Rugby sevens competitions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2004]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Las Vegas]]\n[[Category:Sam Boyd Stadium]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rugby sevens tournament}}\n{{About|the US Sevens rugby tournament|the U.S. national team|United States national rugby sevens team}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n|logo=\n|pixels   = \n|caption=USA Sevens\n|last_season = 2020 USA Sevens <!--\n|current_season = 2021 USA Sevens\n|upcoming_season = 2021 USA Sevens-->\n|sport=Rugby sevens\n|founded= [[2004 USA Sevens|2004]]\n|teams=16\n|ceo =\n|country={{flagicon|USA}} [[United States]]\n|champion= {{ru7|RSA}} \n|most_champs = {{ru7|RSA}} (5 titles)\n|TV = [[ESPN]]\n|website  =[http://www.usasevens.com usasevens.com]\n}}\n\nThe '''USA Sevens''' is a [[rugby sevens]] tournament held annually during March in the United States. The USA Sevens is the largest annual rugby competition in North America, drawing over 60,000 fans, and is broadcast live in the United States by ESPN. The USA Sevens was introduced in 2004, originally in the [[Los Angeles]] suburb of [[Carson, California]]. The event moved to [[San Diego]] in 2007, and from there moved to [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] in 2010. It then spent the entire decade of the 2010s in Las Vegas before returning to Carson in 2020. The USA Sevens tournament features 16 teams representing countries from every inhabited continent, including the host, the [[United States national rugby sevens team|U.S. national team]].\n\nThe USA Sevens is the fifth of ten tournaments on the [[World Rugby Sevens Series]]. The Sevens World Series is played throughout the world at nine other venues: [[Dubai]], [[South Africa]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Singapore]], [[Canada]], [[France]], and [[England]].\n\n[[Image:US Sevens 2012.jpg|thumb|260px|Japan plays New Zealand in the 2012 USA Sevens tournament]]\n\n==Format==\nThe tournament consists of 16 countries participating in 45 matches over a three-day weekend. The 16 teams are divided into four pools of four teams, with seeding determined by finishes in the previous competition in the Sevens World Series. Wins are worth three points, draws two, and losses one. The top two teams from each group progress to the quarterfinals to compete for the Cup (places 1-4) and Plate (places 5-8). The bottom two teams from each group participate in the Bowl (places 9-12) and Shield (places 13-16) competitions.\n\nThrough the 2011\u201312 edition, the sixteen participating teams were the 12 \"core\" members of the [[Sevens World Series]] circuit, along with 4 additional qualifying teams\u2014other teams that qualified multiple times during the 2009\u20132012 span included Japan, Canada, Uruguay and Guyana. Starting with the 2012\u201313 season, the number of core teams increased from 12 to 15, with Canada, Spain and Portugal earning the three new slots.\n\n==Popularity and Growth ==\nThe USA Sevens is the 2nd largest annual rugby competition in North America after the Vancouver 7s in Canada The tournament has grown in popularity since the tournament began in 2004.  In recent years, a number of events have accelerated the surge in popularity, including the announcement in 2009 that rugby would return to the [[Rugby union at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]], the general growth of rugby in the United States, the improved performance of the [[United States national rugby sevens team|U.S. national rugby team]] including their success in reaching the semi-finals of the [[2009 USA Sevens]], and NBC's decision to begin televising the tournament beginning in 2011.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin-left:0.55em; text-align:center; float:right;\"\n|-\n|+ Tournament attendance by year\n|-\n! Year !! Total <br> Attendance !! Highest Day !! Ref\n|-\n| 2010 || 36,600 ||  || <ref name=\"auto\">[http://rugbyamerica.net/?p=3425 \"Editorial: USA 7s Hit the Jackpot in Las Vegas\"], Rugby America, Ted Hardy, January 23, 2014.</ref>\n|-\n| 2011 || 49,909 ||  || <ref name=\"auto1\">Las Vegas Review-Journal, Rugby organizers set lofty goals for 2012, Dec. 31, 2011, http://www.lvrj.com/business/rugby-organizers-set-lofty-goals-for-2012-136471233.html</ref>\n|-\n| 2012 || 64,107 || 30,112 || <ref name=\"auto2\">Kirvin Doak Communications, USA Sevens International Rugby Tournament Returns to Sam Boyd Stadium in Las Vegas for Fourth Consecutive Year, Sep. 11, 2012, {{cite web |url=http://pitchengine.com/kirvindoakcommunications/usa-sevens-international-rugby-tournament-returns-to-sam-boyd-stadium-in-las-vegas-for-fourth-consecutive-year |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916232727/http://pitchengine.com/kirvindoakcommunications/usa-sevens-international-rugby-tournament-returns-to-sam-boyd-stadium-in-las-vegas-for-fourth-consecutive-year |archivedate=2012-09-16 |df= }}</ref> \n|-\n| 2013 || 67,341 || 31,228 || <ref name=\"auto3\">Rugby Mag, Strong Crowds Harbinger of New Direction?, June 9, 2013, http://www.rugbymag.com/goff-on-rugby/8348-goffonrugby-strong-crowds-harbinger-of-new-direction.html</ref> \n|-\n| 2014 || 68,608 || 31,664 || <ref name=\"auto4\">Rugby Mag, USA 7s Attendance Nudges Up Slightly Despite Obstacles, Ja, 26, 2014, http://rugbymag.com/tournaments-special/usa-sevens-tournament/10325-usa-7s-attendance-nudges-up-slightly-despite-obstacles.html</ref>\n|-\n| 2015 || 75,761 || 34,593 || <ref>[http://www.rugbytoday.com/7s/attendance-record-shattered-usa-sevens \"Attendance Record Shattered at USA Sevens\"], Rugby Today, Pat Clifton, February 15, 2015.</ref>\n|-\n| 2016 || 80,138 || 35,716 ||  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbytoday.com/7s/attendance-record-broken-las-vegas-7s|title=Attendance Record Broken at Las Vegas 7s|first=Brett|last=Anker|date=6 March 2016|website=www.rugbytoday.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 || style=\"background:#dfd;\" | 80,691 || style=\"background:#dfd;\" | 35,901 ||  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independentsportsnews.com/2017/03/08/80691-fans-filled-sam-boyd-stadium-2017-usa-sevens-international-rugby-tournament-las-vegas/|title=80,691 Fans Filled Sam Boyd Stadium During the 2017 USA Sevens International Rugby Tournament in Las Vegas - ISN|first=Scott|last=Harrigan|date=8 March 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018 || 65,000* || 30,000 || <ref>https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/motor-sports/nascar/with-nascar-no-longer-booming-are-2-las-vegas-races-too-many-1608519/</ref>\n|-\n|colspan=4 | ''The maximum capacity of Sam Boyd Stadium is 40,000.<br />Green shading represents record highs.<br />*[[2018 Rugby World Cup Sevens|Rugby World Cup Sevens]] held in San Francisco.''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Attendance===\n\nTournament attendance has grown rapidly since its inception in 2004.  The tournament drew 15,800 fans in 2004,<ref>Rugby Mag, GoffonRugby: The Big Deal, Feb. 14, 2011, http://rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=251:goffonrugby-the-big-deal&catid=96:goff-on-rugby&Itemid=292</ref> 25,000 fans in 2007,<ref>Glasgow7s, IRB Sevens Set for Another Record Breaking Year, August 2, 2007, http://www.glasgow7s.com/latest-news/2008-news-archive/55-festival-of-rugby-enjoyed-by-all-at-edinburgh-7s</ref> 35,773 in 2008,<ref name=\"auto\"/> and 37,000 fans in 2009.<ref>Las Vegas Review-Journal, USA Sevens rugby tournament ready to scrum in Las Vegas, Feb. 12, 2010, http://www.lvrj.com/news/usa-sevens-rugby-tournament-ready-to-scrum-in-las-vegas-84211412.html.</ref>\n\nThe tournament switched to a three-day format in 2011.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> The 2012 tournament's second-day attendance of 30,112 set a new record for the largest crowd to watch a rugby event in the United States.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> The 2013 tournament broke attendance records again, with total attendance of 67,341.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> The 2014 tournament again saw record attendance, with 68,608 fans, despite the fact that the tournament had been moved to January to avoid the 2014 Winter Olympics.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n===Media coverage===\nThe profile and visibility of the USA Sevens has increased in the United States since NBC began broadcasting the tournament in 2011, marking the first time that the tournament had live television coverage on network TV in the United States. [[NBC Sports]] and [[Universal Sports]] broadcast eight hours of live coverage of the 2011 tournament, including 4 hours of coverage on NBC.  NBC increased its television coverage for the 2012 tournament, showing 10 hours of live coverage, including 4 hours on [[NBC]] and 4 hours on [[NBC Sports]].<ref>TV by the Numbers, [http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/02/09/10-hours-of-live-coverage-of-hsbc-sevens-rugby-this-weekend-on-nbc-nbc-sports-network-and-universal-sports/119331/ 10 Hours of Live Coverage of HSBC Sevens Rugby This Weekend], Feb. 9, 2012.</ref> The 2012 USA Sevens earned strong ratings of 0.7 on NBC, beating other popular sports events that weekend such as the Detroit v. Philadelphia NHL game (0.4) and the Alabama v. LSU basketball game (0.3).<ref>Sports Media Watch, Weekly Sports TV Ratings, Feb 22, 2012, http://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2012/02/weekly-sports-tv-ratings-february-11-february-17/</ref> NBC again increased its TV coverage in 2013, with 16 hours of coverage across three channels, including 4 hours on [[NBC]] and 6 hours on [[NBC Sports]].<ref>TV by the numbers, NBC, [http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/02/07/nbc-nbc-sports-network-and-universal-sports-combine-to-deliver-more-than-16-hours-of-usa-sevens-vegas/168616/ NBC Sports Network and Universal Sports Combine to Deliver More Than 16 Hours of USA Sevens Vegas], Feb. 7, 2013.</ref> The 2014 USA Sevens drew ratings of 0.7 on Saturday and 1.0 on Sunday.<ref>[http://www.rugbytoday.com/tournaments/tv-ratings-usa-7s-rise \"TV Ratings for USA 7s Rise\"], Rugby Today, January 28, 2014.</ref> The 2016 USA Sevens had 7 hours of TV coverage across NBCSN and NBC, but only 1 hour on NBC.\n\nNBC Sports has displayed an increased interest in broadcasting rugby since the [[International Olympic Committee]]'s announcement in 2009 that [[Rugby union at the Summer Olympics|rugby would return to the Summer Olympics]] in 2016.<ref name=\"auto5\">Adweek, NBC Lines Up 4 Sponsors for USA Rugby Tourney, Feb. 8, 2011, http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising-branding/nbc-lines-4-sponsors-usa-rugby-tourney-125685</ref> NBC Sports has recognized that its partnership with USA Sevens to broadcast the tournament will help grow the sport of rugby in the United States.<ref>Inside the Games, Match timings switched as rugby sevens televised live across USA for first time, Jan. 21, 2011, http://www.insidethegames.biz/sports/summer/rugby-sevens/11712-match-timings-switched-as-rugby-sevens-televised-live-across-usa-for-first-time</ref>\n\n===Sponsors===\nFueled in part by the publicity generated by the NBC broadcasts and rugby's return to the Olympics, the USA Sevens has been successful in lining up several blue-chip corporate sponsors. For the 2011 tournament, sponsors included Bridgestone, Toyota, Subway and ADT.<ref name=\"auto5\"/> The tournament was similarly successful in landing commercial sponsors for 2012, including Adidas, Pepsi, DHL, Subway and others.<ref>USA Sevens Rugby, Leading brands have sponsorship in rugby, http://www.usasevens.com/las-vegas/event/sponsors/</ref>\n\nEffective with the 2010\u201311 series, the London-based global financial services company [[HSBC]] became the title sponsor of the overall IRB Sevens World Series.\n\n==History==\nThe USA Sevens tournament has been a part of the [[World Rugby Sevens Series]] every year since its 2004 debut.  This makes the USA Sevens tournament one of the longer running consecutive hosts on the circuit.\n\nThe USA Sevens debuted at the Home Depot Center, now known as [[Dignity Health Sports Park]], in the Los Angeles suburb of [[Carson, California]] in February 2004.  This competition marked the first time the United States ever hosted an official IRB event of international importance.  USA Rugby was awarded the right to host the USA Sevens for three years, in part because rugby was recognized as one of the fastest growing team sports in the U.S.<ref>USA Rugby, TEAM ROC USA SEVENS Brings World Rugby Series to U.S., Jan. 28, 2004, http://web.usarugby.org/cgi-bin/viadesto/press/display.pl?releaseId=671</ref>\n\nIn 2005, USA Rugby sold a 90% interest in USA Sevens, LLC to United World Sports, LLC, with USA Rugby retaining the remaining 10% ownership interest.<ref>See USA Rugby December 31, 2010 Consolidated Financial Statements, available at www.usarugby.org</ref> In August 2006, [[USA Rugby]] and the International Rugby Board renewed the contract for the USA Sevens to remain in the IRB Sevens World Series.\n\nThe USA Sevens tournament was held from 2007 to 2009 in San Diego at [[Petco Park]], the home field of the San Diego Padres of Major League Baseball. [[San Diego]] was an appealing location because the average high temperature in San Diego in February is a balmy 72&nbsp;\u00b0F (22&nbsp;\u00b0C).\n\nLas Vegas then won the right to host the annual event beginning in 2010, beating out competition from San Francisco, [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], and [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]].<ref>Las Vegas Review-Journal, EDITORIAL: Successful scrum, Jan. 29, 2014, http://www.reviewjournal.com/opinion/editorial-successful-scrum</ref> In 2015, World Rugby reached an agreement with USA Rugby and with the tournament's organizers: World Rugby would continue to place the USA Sevens tournament in Las Vegas if the tournament organizers agreed to widen the field at Sam Boyd Stadium and install approved artificial turf.<ref>[http://www.goffrugbyreport.com/news/successful-usa-7s-whats-next \"Successful USA 7s, But What's Next?\"], Goff Rugby Report, Alex Goff, February 15, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe USA Sevens was been a financial success during its run in Las Vegas, partly because its venue of [[Sam Boyd Stadium]] was surrounded by playing fields. This allowed the complex to host the Las Vegas Invitational, a major rugby union event involving club, school, and [[College rugby|university]] teams, alongside the USA Sevens. During the USA Sevens' run in Las Vegas, the entry fee for the Invitational has included tickets to the USA Sevens, providing a large built-in attendance base.<ref name=Province>{{cite news|url=https://theprovince.com/sports/rugby/leaving-las-vegas-usa-sevens-to-move-for-2020|title=Leaving Las Vegas: USA Sevens to move for 2020|first=Patrick|last=Johnston|newspaper=[[The Province]] |location=[[Vancouver]] |date=2019-01-29|accessdate=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[Las Vegas Raiders|Oakland Raiders]] were given permission by the [[National Football League|NFL]] to [[Oakland Raiders relocation to Las Vegas|relocate to Las Vegas]], with the team to play in a [[Allegiant Stadium|new 60,000-capacity stadium]] on a plot of derelict land near the Las Vegas Strip. Due to the fact that $750 million of the construction costs was expected to come in the form of public funding, a deal was thrashed out to allow the [[UNLV Rebels football]] team of the local University of Nevada, Las Vegas to move in as co-tenants of the new stadium. This meant that Sam Boyd Stadium faces an uncertain future with multiple sources suggesting that it would be demolished. In March 2018, [[United World Sports]] CEO Jon Prusmack stated his intention on initiating talks with the Raiders over the next few months to allow the USA Sevens to use the new Raiders stadium for future tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mattrybaltowski/2018/03/07/fresh-off-stunning-usa-sevens-win-rugby-exec-encouraged-by-potential-move-to-raiders-new-stadium/#11ef2b28b90a|title=Fresh Off Stunning USA Sevens Win, Rugby Exec Encouraged By Potential Move to Raiders' New Stadium|first=Matt|last=Rybaltowski|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2019, ''[[The Province]]'', the main newspaper in [[Vancouver]], reported that the then-upcoming [[2019 USA Sevens]] would be the last in Las Vegas, at least for the immediate future. At the time, [[World Rugby]] was preparing to announce the hosts for the Sevens Series events for its next four-year cycle, starting with 2019\u201320 and running through 2022\u201323. Reasons cited were stadium issues and poor living environment at the team hotels. Possible options were a return to San Diego, or moves to [[San Francisco]] (which hosted the [[2018 Rugby World Cup Sevens]]) or [[Miami]].<ref name=Province/> WR ultimately announced that the event would return to its original home of Dignity Health Sports Park for at least the 2020 event.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.world.rugby/sevens-series/news/439736  |title=Schedule announced for HSBC World Rugby Sevens Series 2020 |publisher=World Rugby |date=August 8, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808171636/https://www.world.rugby/sevens-series/news/439736 |archivedate=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nApart from the uncertain future of Sam Boyd Stadium, its playing field had been the source of many issues. During the first years of the event's run in Las Vegas, the stadium's standard artificial pitch was used, leading to many safety-related concerns. Some of these concerns were alleviated with the installation of temporary grass surfaces for the 2017\u20132019 events, but other safety issues inherent to the stadium's design remained. Sam Boyd Stadium was built for American football, a sport with a playing field (including the end zones) that is approximately the same length as a standard rugby pitch but is nearly 20 meters narrower. Because of this, the pitch in Las Vegas was noticeably narrower than at other series stops, with team benches unusually close to the touchlines.<ref name=Province/>\n\n==Results==\n\n===Results by year===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width: 100%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2 width=5%|Year \n!rowspan=2 width=12%|Host \n|width=1% rowspan=20|<!-- INCREMENT WHEN ADDING A ROW -->\n!colspan=3|Cup Final \n|width=1% rowspan=20|<!-- INCREMENT WHEN ADDING A ROW -->\n!colspan=3|